window.MM['oph_p2_cornea'] = [
{"q":"A contact lens wearer presents with severe ocular pain, photophobia, purulent discharge, and a rapidly progressive corneal ulcer with greenish exudate. Which organism is most likely responsible?","o":["Staphylococcus epidermidis","Pseudomonas aeruginosa","Herpes simplex virus","Candida albicans","Streptococcus pneumoniae"],"a":1,"e":"Pseudomonas aeruginosa is strongly associated with contact lens-related microbial keratitis and may rapidly produce corneal melting and perforation.<br><br>Of its aggressive destructive nature and characteristic greenish discharge. Rapidly progressive Pseudomonas corneal melt in a lens wearer is a high-stakes emergency pattern.<br><br>Herpes simplex virus (C) typically produces dendritic epithelial ulcers rather than rapidly suppurative purulent keratitis with green exudate.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal ulcer classically demonstrates a dendritic branching pattern with terminal bulbs on fluorescein staining?","o":["Herpes simplex keratitis","Mooren ulcer","Fungal ulcer","Marginal keratitis","Neurotrophic ulcer"],"a":0,"e":"Herpes simplex epithelial keratitis classically presents with branching dendritic ulcers containing terminal bulbs that stain with fluorescein.<br><br>Fungal ulcers (C) typically have feathery margins and satellite lesions rather than dendritic branching.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A farmer develops a painful corneal ulcer after trauma with vegetative matter. Slit lamp shows feathery margins and satellite lesions. Which diagnosis is most likely?","o":["Bacterial keratitis","Viral keratitis","Fungal keratitis","Neuroparalytic keratitis","Marginal ulcer"],"a":2,"e":"Trauma with vegetative matter is a classic predisposing factor for fungal keratitis, especially caused by filamentous fungi such as Aspergillus or Fusarium.<br><br>Bacterial keratitis (A) usually produces dense suppurative infiltrates without characteristic feathery edges.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal ulcer is characteristically associated with hypopyon that remains mobile?","o":["Herpetic ulcer","Mooren ulcer","Fungal ulcer","Serpiginous ulcer","Marginal ulcer"],"a":3,"e":"Pneumococcal serpiginous corneal ulcer often produces hypopyon that remains mobile because it is sterile and inflammatory rather than purulent initially.<br><br>Of their creeping edge and rapid spread.<br><br>Herpetic ulcers (A) typically produce dendritic lesions rather than serpiginous suppuration.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which stain is most commonly used to identify fungal filaments in corneal scrapings?","o":["Gram stain","Ziehl-Neelsen stain","Giemsa stain","Potassium hydroxide preparation","India ink preparation"],"a":3,"e":"KOH wet mount rapidly dissolves cellular debris while preserving fungal hyphae, making it highly useful in fungal keratitis diagnosis.<br><br>Ziehl-Neelsen stain (B) is primarily used for acid-fast bacilli rather than fungal filaments.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which feature most strongly suggests fungal rather than bacterial corneal ulcer?","o":["Feathery ulcer margins","Rapid perforation within hours","Dense purulent discharge","Marked conjunctival chemosis","Greenish exudate"],"a":0,"e":"Fungal ulcers classically demonstrate dry elevated infiltrates with feathery borders and satellite lesions.<br><br>Greenish exudate (E) strongly suggests Pseudomonas infection instead.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient with corneal anesthesia develops a persistent nonhealing epithelial defect. Which ulcer type is most likely?","o":["Neurotrophic ulcer","Mooren ulcer","Marginal ulcer","Phlyctenular ulcer","Dendritic ulcer"],"a":0,"e":"Neurotrophic ulcers result from impaired corneal sensation leading to defective epithelial healing and persistent epithelial defects.<br><br>Common causes include trigeminal nerve damage and herpes simplex infection.<br><br>Mooren ulcer (B) is a painful peripheral autoimmune ulcer rather than an anesthetic nonhealing defect.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which organism is most commonly associated with rapidly progressive contact lens-related keratitis?","o":["Candida albicans","Pseudomonas aeruginosa","Herpes zoster virus","Bacillus anthracis","Corynebacterium diphtheriae"],"a":1,"e":"Pseudomonas produces proteolytic enzymes that rapidly destroy corneal stroma and may cause perforation within 24-48 hours.<br><br>Rapidly progressive Pseudomonas corneal melt in a lens wearer is a high-stakes emergency pattern.<br><br>Candida (A) more commonly causes indolent fungal keratitis.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal ulcer classically begins as a dendritic ulcer and later enlarges into a geographic ulcer after steroid misuse?","o":["Fungal ulcer","Marginal ulcer","Herpetic ulcer","Mooren ulcer","Neuroparalytic ulcer"],"a":2,"e":"Improper topical steroid use in herpes simplex epithelial keratitis may enlarge dendritic lesions into geographic ulcers.<br><br>Marginal ulcers (B) are hypersensitivity lesions associated with blepharitis rather than steroid-induced geographic ulceration.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which investigation is most essential before initiating treatment in microbial keratitis?","o":["Gonioscopy","Corneal scraping for microscopy and culture","Automated perimetry","OCT macula","Schirmer testing"],"a":1,"e":"Corneal scraping permits identification of causative organisms and guides targeted antimicrobial therapy.<br><br>Microbiological diagnosis is especially important in severe, atypical, or treatment-resistant ulcers.<br><br>Schirmer testing (E) evaluates tear production and has no primary role in infectious keratitis diagnosis.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal ulcer is typically associated with severe pain disproportionate to clinical findings?","o":["Mooren ulcer","Neurotrophic ulcer","Marginal ulcer","Exposure keratitis","Bullous keratopathy"],"a":0,"e":"Mooren ulcer is a painful peripheral autoimmune ulcerative keratitis often associated with progressive stromal destruction.<br><br>Neurotrophic ulcers (B) often have reduced pain because of impaired corneal sensation.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which feature is most characteristic of bacterial corneal ulcer?","o":["Dense suppurative stromal infiltrate","Satellite lesions","Dry raised infiltrate","Corneal anesthesia","Ring infiltrate only"],"a":0,"e":"Bacterial keratitis commonly presents with dense suppurative infiltrate, stromal edema, mucopurulent discharge, and marked inflammation.<br><br>Rapid recognition is important because untreated bacterial ulcers may perforate quickly.<br><br>Satellite lesions (B) are more suggestive of fungal keratitis.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which condition is a major predisposing factor for exposure keratitis and ulceration?","o":["Entropion","Lagophthalmos","Myopia","Blepharophimosis","Hypermetropia"],"a":1,"e":"Lagophthalmos prevents complete eyelid closure, exposing the cornea to desiccation and secondary ulceration.<br><br>Exposure keratopathy is commonly associated with facial nerve palsy and proptosis.<br><br>Entropion (A) causes trichiasis-related irritation rather than primary exposure keratitis.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which organism is classically associated with ring-shaped corneal infiltrate in contact lens users?","o":["Aspergillus","Acanthamoeba","Staphylococcus aureus","Pneumococcus","Herpes simplex virus"],"a":1,"e":"Acanthamoeba keratitis is strongly associated with contact lens wear and may produce severe pain with ring infiltrates.<br><br>Pneumococcus (D) typically causes serpiginous ulcers rather than ring infiltrates.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal ulcer is strongly associated with chronic blepharitis and staphylococcal hypersensitivity?","o":["Marginal ulcer","Mooren ulcer","Neurotrophic ulcer","Herpetic ulcer","Fungal ulcer"],"a":0,"e":"Marginal ulcers result from hypersensitivity reaction to staphylococcal antigens associated with chronic blepharitis.<br><br>They typically occur near the limbus separated from it by a clear zone.<br><br>Herpetic ulcers (D) produce dendritic lesions rather than peripheral hypersensitivity infiltrates.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which topical medication is contraindicated in active epithelial herpes simplex keratitis?","o":["Cycloplegics","Lubricants","Topical steroids","Oral acyclovir","Antibiotic prophylaxis"],"a":2,"e":"Topical corticosteroids may worsen epithelial herpes simplex keratitis by promoting viral replication and geographic ulcer formation.<br><br>Cycloplegics (A) may be useful for pain relief in associated iridocyclitis.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal ulcer commonly produces satellite lesions?","o":["Fungal ulcer","Bacterial ulcer","Neuroparalytic ulcer","Marginal ulcer","Dendritic ulcer"],"a":0,"e":"Satellite lesions surrounding the main infiltrate are classic signs of fungal keratitis.<br><br>These lesions result from secondary fungal implantation into adjacent corneal stroma.<br><br>Dendritic ulcers (E) are characteristic of herpes simplex infection rather than fungal keratitis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which clinical feature strongly suggests impending corneal perforation?","o":["Mild epithelial edema","Descemetocele formation","Small superficial punctate staining","Peripheral vascularization only","Arcus senilis"],"a":1,"e":"Descemetocele occurs when stromal destruction leaves only Descemet membrane intact, indicating imminent perforation risk.<br><br>Recognition of descemetocele is essential because urgent surgical intervention may be required.<br><br>Arcus senilis (E) is a benign peripheral lipid deposition unrelated to ulcer perforation.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal ulcer classically spreads serpiginously over the cornea?","o":["Viral dendritic ulcer","Marginal ulcer","Neurotrophic ulcer","Pneumococcal ulcer","Exposure ulcer"],"a":3,"e":"Pneumococcal ulcers often spread with a creeping serpiginous edge accompanied by hypopyon formation.<br><br>Marginal ulcers (B) are peripheral hypersensitivity lesions rather than aggressively spreading ulcers.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient with severe pain disproportionate to signs, ring infiltrate, and contact lens misuse most likely has:","o":["Acanthamoeba keratitis","Fungal keratitis","Herpes simplex keratitis","Marginal keratitis","Neurotrophic ulcer"],"a":0,"e":"Acanthamoeba keratitis classically presents with severe pain out of proportion to examination findings and ring stromal infiltrates.<br><br>Herpes simplex keratitis (C) usually presents with dendritic ulcers rather than ring infiltrates with extreme pain.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 25-year-old contact lens wearer presents with severe pain, photophobia, and a large central corneal ulcer with hypopyon. Corneal scraping grows a gram-negative rod. Which organism is most likely responsible?","o":["Pseudomonas aeruginosa","Staphylococcus epidermidis","Streptococcus pneumoniae","Moraxella lacunata","Acanthamoeba castellanii"],"a":0,"e":"Pseudomonas aeruginosa is the most common cause of contact lens-related bacterial keratitis; it produces a rapidly destructive ulcer with grey-green discharge and hypopyon due to potent exotoxin production.<br><br>Overnight lens wear creates hypoxic corneal conditions facilitating Pseudomonas adherence; the organism can perforate the cornea within 24 to 48 hours without treatment.<br><br>Staphylococcus epidermidis (B) causes less aggressive ulcers; Streptococcus pneumoniae (C) causes serpiginous ulcer; Moraxella (D) causes indolent inferior ulcers; Acanthamoeba (E) causes ring infiltrate with disproportionate pain.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 60-year-old farmer presents with a corneal ulcer after injury with plant material. Slit-lamp shows a dry rough-surfaced ulcer with feathery edges and satellite lesions. Which organism is most likely responsible?","o":["Pseudomonas aeruginosa","Fusarium solani","Acanthamoeba species","Herpes simplex virus","Streptococcus pneumoniae"],"a":1,"e":"Fusarium solani is the most common cause of fungal keratitis following vegetative trauma; the dry rough surface, feathery margins, and satellite lesions are pathognomonic of filamentous fungal keratitis.<br><br>KOH mount reveals septate hyphae; natamycin 5% is the treatment of choice as it provides reliable filamentous fungal coverage.<br><br>Pseudomonas (A) causes rapidly liquefying bacterial ulcer; Acanthamoeba (C) causes ring infiltrate; herpes simplex (D) causes dendritic ulcer with terminal bulbs; Streptococcus pneumoniae (E) causes serpiginous bacterial ulcer.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 35-year-old presents with a dendritic corneal ulcer with terminal bulbs on fluorescein staining and reduced corneal sensation. Which is the most appropriate first-line treatment?","o":["Natamycin eye drops","Ciprofloxacin eye drops","Topical acyclovir ointment","Topical steroids alone","Amphotericin eye drops"],"a":2,"e":"A dendritic ulcer with terminal bulbs and reduced sensation is pathognomonic of herpes simplex keratitis; topical acyclovir 3% ointment five times daily for two weeks inhibits viral DNA polymerase halting epithelial replication.<br><br>Steroids are absolutely contraindicated in active epithelial disease as they accelerate viral replication causing geographic ulcer enlargement.<br><br>Natamycin (A) and amphotericin (E) treat fungal keratitis; ciprofloxacin (B) treats bacterial keratitis; topical steroids alone (D) are contraindicated in active herpetic epithelial disease.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 45-year-old immunocompromised patient develops disc-shaped stromal corneal oedema with keratic precipitates beneath it following a cold sore recurrence. What is the most likely diagnosis?","o":["Fungal stromal keratitis","Acanthamoeba keratitis","Bacterial suppurative keratitis","Herpes simplex disciform keratitis","Marginal"],"a":3,"e":"Herpes simplex disciform keratitis represents immune-mediated stromal inflammation not active viral replication; disc-shaped stromal oedema with intact epithelium and keratic precipitates beneath are the classic features.<br><br>Topical steroids combined with antiviral cover are the treatment of choice; long-term oral acyclovir reduces recurrence frequency significantly.<br><br>Fungal keratitis (A) follows vegetative trauma; Acanthamoeba (B) causes ring infiltrate; bacterial keratitis (C) causes suppurative ulcer with discharge; marginal keratitis (E) is peripheral and associated with blepharitis.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 30-year-old contact lens wearer with a history of swimming presents with severe disproportionate pain, perineural infiltrates, and a ring-shaped stromal infiltrate. Which organism is responsible?","o":["Fusarium solani","Pseudomonas aeruginosa","Herpes simplex virus","Streptococcus viridans","Acanthamoeba species"],"a":4,"e":"Acanthamoeba keratitis classically presents with pain disproportionate to clinical signs, perineural infiltrates along corneal nerves, ring infiltrate, and a history of contact lens wear combined with water exposure.<br><br>Diagnosis is confirmed by confocal microscopy revealing double-walled cysts; treatment involves prolonged polyhexamethylene biguanide and chlorhexidine drops for six to twelve months.<br><br>Fusarium (A) follows vegetative trauma; Pseudomonas (B) causes rapidly progressive bacterial ulcer; herpes simplex (C) causes dendritic ulcer; Streptococcus viridans (D) causes bacterial keratitis without ring infiltrate.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 65-year-old with chronic blepharitis develops a small peripheral corneal ulcer at the 2 o'clock position with a clear zone between the ulcer and limbus. There is no discharge. What is the most likely diagnosis?","o":["Marginal keratitis","Mooren's ulcer","Fungal keratitis","Bacterial keratitis","Exposure keratitis"],"a":0,"e":"Marginal keratitis is a hypersensitivity reaction to staphylococcal exotoxins from chronic blepharitis; the peripheral location with a clear zone separating the ulcer from the limbus and absence of organisms are diagnostic.<br><br>Lid hygiene combined with topical antibiotic-steroid drops resolves the infiltrate rapidly; recurrence is prevented only by adequate long-term blepharitis control.<br><br>Mooren's ulcer (B) has no clear zone and progresses circumferentially; fungal keratitis (C) follows vegetative trauma; bacterial keratitis (D) has organisms on scraping; exposure keratitis (E) affects the inferior interpalpebral zone.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 55-year-old presents with a painful progressive peripheral corneal ulcer with undermined edges spreading circumferentially. No infectious cause is found. Systemic vasculitis workup is negative. What is the most likely diagnosis?","o":["Marginal keratitis","Mooren's ulcer","Fungal keratitis","Rosacea keratitis","Herpes zoster keratitis"],"a":1,"e":"Mooren's ulcer is an idiopathic painful progressive peripheral ulceration with undermined edges and circumferential spread; it is a diagnosis of exclusion after infectious and systemic autoimmune causes are ruled out.<br><br>Unilateral disease in older patients responds better to treatment; bilateral disease in younger patients is more aggressive requiring systemic immunosuppression.<br><br>Marginal keratitis (A) is small and associated with blepharitis; fungal keratitis (C) has an infectious cause; rosacea keratitis (D) occurs with facial rosacea; herpes zoster keratitis (E) follows dermatomal rash.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 40-year-old presents with a corneal ulcer following a road traffic accident. Corneal scraping grows gram-positive cocci in clusters. Which organism is most likely responsible?","o":["Streptococcus pneumoniae","Pseudomonas aeruginosa","Moraxella lacunata","Staphylococcus aureus","Fusarium solani"],"a":3,"e":"Staphylococcus aureus causes bacterial keratitis following corneal trauma; it produces a well-defined oval stromal ulcer with mucopurulent discharge and hypopyon; gram-positive cocci in clusters confirm staphylococcal aetiology.<br><br>MRSA strains require vancomycin confirmed by sensitivity testing; standard strains are treated with fortified cefazolin or topical fluoroquinolone drops.<br><br>Streptococcus pneumoniae (A) appears as diplococci in pairs; Pseudomonas (B) is gram-negative; Moraxella (C) is gram-negative diplococcus; Fusarium (E) is a fungus not a bacterium.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 50-year-old alcoholic presents with an indolent inferior corneal ulcer. He has poor nutrition and personal hygiene. Scraping shows gram-negative diplococci. Which organism is responsible?","o":["Pseudomonas aeruginosa","Neisseria gonorrhoeae","Streptococcus pneumoniae","Moraxella lacunata","Haemophilus influenzae"],"a":3,"e":"Moraxella lacunata causes indolent inferior corneal ulcers classically in debilitated patients including alcoholics and the malnourished; the slow-progressing ulcer with minimal inflammation and gram-negative diplococci on scraping are characteristic.<br><br>Treatment with topical fluoroquinolones is effective; addressing underlying nutritional and social factors prevents recurrence.<br><br>Pseudomonas (A) causes aggressive rapidly progressive ulceration; Neisseria gonorrhoeae (B) causes hyperacute keratitis with copious discharge; Streptococcus pneumoniae (C) is gram-positive; Haemophilus (E) causes keratitis in children not debilitated adults.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 28-year-old soft contact lens wearer presents with severe pain and photophobia. Slit-lamp shows linear perineural infiltrates tracking along corneal nerves and a partially formed ring infiltrate. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Pseudomonas keratitis","Fungal keratitis","Marginal keratitis","Herpetic stromal keratitis","Acanthamoeba keratitis"],"a":4,"e":"Perineural infiltrates tracking along corneal nerve trunks are pathognomonic of Acanthamoeba keratitis; the pain is disproportionately severe relative to early slit-lamp findings; contact lens wear with water exposure is the classic risk factor.<br><br>Confocal microscopy revealing double-walled cysts is the most rapid diagnostic tool; early diagnosis before ring infiltrate formation significantly improves prognosis.<br><br>Pseudomonas (A) causes rapidly destructive bacterial ulcer; fungal keratitis (B) follows vegetative trauma; marginal keratitis (C) is peripheral and blepharitis-associated; herpetic stromal keratitis (D) causes disc-shaped oedema not perineural infiltrates.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 70-year-old presents with a serpiginous corneal ulcer advancing across the cornea from the limbus with a large hypopyon and undermined stroma. Which organism classically causes this pattern?","o":["Streptococcus pneumoniae","Pseudomonas aeruginosa","Fusarium solani","Acanthamoeba castellanii","Herpes simplex virus"],"a":0,"e":"Streptococcus pneumoniae causes the classic serpiginous hypopyon ulcer; it begins peripherally advancing across the cornea with undermined edges and prominent hypopyon; it was historically the most common cause of bacterial keratitis.<br><br>The organism is associated with dacryocystitis as a predisposing source; treatment is intensive topical penicillin or fluoroquinolone drops.<br><br>Pseudomonas (B) causes rapidly liquefying central ulcer; Fusarium (C) causes fungal keratitis with hyphate margins; Acanthamoeba (D) causes ring infiltrate; herpes simplex (E) causes dendritic or geographic ulcers.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A corneal scraping from a patient with suspected bacterial keratitis shows gram-positive lancet-shaped diplococci with a capsule. Which organism does this indicate?","o":["Staphylococcus aureus","Pseudomonas aeruginosa","Moraxella lacunata","Streptococcus pneumoniae","Neisseria gonorrhoeae"],"a":3,"e":"Streptococcus pneumoniae appears as gram-positive lancet-shaped diplococci with a polysaccharide capsule; this morphology from a corneal scraping in a patient with a serpiginous hypopyon ulcer confirms pneumococcal keratitis and guides antibiotic selection.<br><br>The organism is bile-soluble and optochin-sensitive aiding laboratory identification; intensive topical penicillin or fluoroquinolone is the treatment of choice.<br><br>Staphylococcus aureus (A) appears as gram-positive cocci in clusters; Moraxella (C) is gram-negative; Pseudomonas (B) is gram-negative rod; Neisseria gonorrhoeae (E) is gram-negative diplococcus inside neutrophils.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 22-year-old sexually active male presents with sudden severe purulent conjunctivitis and corneal ulceration. The discharge reaccumulates within minutes of wiping. Gram stain shows gram-negative intracellular diplococci. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Pseudomonas keratitis","Chlamydial keratitis","Gonococcal keratitis","Staphylococcal keratitis","Moraxella keratitis"],"a":2,"e":"Neisseria gonorrhoeae causes hyperacute keratitis with profuse purulent discharge reaccumulating within minutes; gram-negative intracellular diplococci within neutrophils confirm the diagnosis; the organism penetrates intact corneal epithelium through potent protease production.<br><br>Systemic ceftriaxone is required due to beta-lactamase-mediated penicillin resistance; concurrent Chlamydia co-infection must always be excluded and sexual contacts traced.<br><br>Pseudomonas (A) affects contact lens wearers; chlamydial keratitis (B) causes micropannus and follicular conjunctivitis; staphylococcal (D) does not cause hyperacute copious discharge; Moraxella (E) causes indolent inferior ulcers in debilitated patients.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 35-year-old rice farmer presents with a corneal ulcer after paddy field work. KOH mount shows non-septate broad hyphae with right-angle branching. Which organism is responsible?","o":["Fusarium solani","Aspergillus fumigatus","Candida albicans","Mucor species","Curvularia lunata"],"a":3,"e":"Non-septate broad hyphae with right-angle branching on KOH mount are the classic morphological features of Mucorales; corneal mucormycosis occurs following trauma in agricultural settings or in immunocompromised patients and requires amphotericin B and surgical debridement.<br><br>The non-septate wide-angle branching distinguishes Mucorales from Aspergillus and Fusarium which are septate with acute-angle branching.<br><br>Fusarium (A) is septate with acute-angle branching; Aspergillus (B) is septate with dichotomous acute branching; Candida (C) produces pseudohyphae and budding yeast; Curvularia (E) is a pigmented septate dematiaceous fungus.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 55-year-old patient with trigeminal nerve palsy from a cerebellopontine angle tumour develops a painless inferior corneal ulcer despite an intact blink reflex and normal tear production. What type of keratitis is this?","o":["Exposure keratitis","Marginal keratitis","Neurotrophic keratitis","Bacterial keratitis","Neuroparalytic keratitis"],"a":4,"e":"Neuroparalytic keratitis results from trigeminal nerve damage abolishing corneal sensation; loss of trophic neuropeptides including substance P causes epithelial breakdown and stromal melting despite intact blink reflex and tear production.<br><br>The painless nature is dangerous as patients present late; tarsorrhaphy, amniotic membrane grafting, and intensive lubrication are the mainstays of management. Corneal graft rejection lines and management are a heavily emphasised post-keratoplasty theme.<br><br>Exposure keratitis (A) results from lagophthalmos not trigeminal damage; marginal keratitis (B) is peripheral and blepharitis-associated; neurotrophic (C) is synonymous but option E is more specific for trigeminal palsy; bacterial keratitis (D) has an infectious aetiology.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 48-year-old woman with rheumatoid arthritis develops a painful peripheral corneal ulcer with rapid stromal melting and descemetocele formation. No organisms are grown on scraping. What is the most likely diagnosis?","o":["Peripheral ulcerative keratitis","Mooren's ulcer","Marginal keratitis","Fungal keratitis","Bacterial keratitis"],"a":0,"e":"Peripheral ulcerative keratitis in rheumatoid arthritis is an immune-mediated condition driven by circulating immune complexes and matrix metalloproteinases causing rapid stromal melting and descemetocele formation without an infectious cause.<br><br>Systemic immunosuppression with methotrexate or cyclophosphamide is required; descemetocele requires urgent tectonic keratoplasty or tissue adhesive to prevent perforation. Fungal keratitis with feathery margins after vegetative trauma is a recurring differentiator.<br><br>Mooren's ulcer (B) has no associated systemic disease; marginal keratitis (C) is small without stromal melting; fungal keratitis (D) has an infectious aetiology; bacterial keratitis (E) grows organisms on scraping.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient with a dendritic corneal ulcer is stained with rose bengal. The dye stains the edges of the dendrite and surrounding cells. What does rose bengal staining specifically indicate?","o":["Active viral replication zones","Devitalised cells lacking mucin cover","Bowman layer disruption only","Stromal keratocyte activation","Sites of corneal neovascularisation"],"a":1,"e":"Rose bengal stains devitalised and dead epithelial cells lacking their protective mucin layer; in herpetic dendritic ulcers it stains the edges and surrounding dyskeratotic cells, revealing the full extent of the lesion beyond what fluorescein shows.<br><br>Fluorescein stains only where epithelium is absent; rose bengal complements fluorescein by revealing damaged cells at the margins, aiding diagnosis of early herpetic keratitis and dry eye disease.<br><br>Active viral replication zones (A) are not specifically identified by rose bengal; Bowman layer disruption (C) requires slit-lamp assessment; stromal keratocyte activation (D) is not detectable by surface vital dye; corneal neovascularisation (E) is assessed by slit-lamp not vital dye.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 30-year-old presents with herpes zoster ophthalmicus following a V1 dermatomal vesicular rash. Slit-lamp shows a pseudo-dendritic corneal lesion. How does this differ from a herpes simplex dendrite?","o":["Larger with true ulceration","Smaller with terminal bulbs","Deeper stromal involvement initially","Elevated mucous plaque without true ulceration","Associated with endothelial disease only"],"a":3,"e":"Herpes zoster pseudo-dendrites are elevated mucous plaques that stain poorly with fluorescein but well with rose bengal; they lack true epithelial ulceration and terminal bulbs distinguishing them from herpes simplex dendrites; this distinction critically changes management.<br><br>HZO is treated with systemic acyclovir or valacyclovir; topical steroids may be required for stromal involvement; zoster causes more frequent neurotrophic complications than simplex.<br><br>Larger with true ulceration (A) describes herpes simplex; smaller with terminal bulbs (B) also describes simplex features; deeper stromal involvement initially (C) is not the distinguishing pseudo-dendritic feature; endothelial disease only (E) is a later complication.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A corneal ulcer patient was started on topical steroids by a general practitioner. On review the ulcer has dramatically enlarged into a geographic pattern. What was the most likely original diagnosis?","o":["Fungal keratitis","Acanthamoeba keratitis","Bacterial keratitis","Herpetic epithelial keratitis","Marginal keratitis"],"a":3,"e":"Topical steroids dramatically accelerate herpes simplex viral replication in active epithelial disease; the dendrite enlarges into a large geographic ulcer as the virus spreads uncontrolled; this is one of the most dangerous and common errors in corneal ulcer management.<br><br>Antiviral therapy must be started immediately and steroids carefully tapered; steroids are reserved only for immune-mediated stromal disease under strict antiviral cover.<br><br>Fungal keratitis (A) worsens with steroids but does not produce geographic epithelial pattern; Acanthamoeba (B) worsens but produces ring infiltrate; bacterial keratitis (C) worsens through different mechanisms; marginal keratitis (E) improves with steroids rather than worsening.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 38-year-old presents with recurrent corneal ulcers, lid margin vesicles, and reduced bilateral corneal sensation. Which investigation most specifically confirms the diagnosis?","o":["Corneal topography mapping","Conjunctival swab culture","Anterior segment OCT","Tear film osmolarity","Corneal confocal microscopy"],"a":4,"e":"In vivo corneal confocal microscopy detects intraepithelial viral inclusions, activated keratocytes, and dendritic cell infiltration in herpetic keratitis; it provides real-time structural information without tissue sampling and monitors treatment response.<br><br>Reduced bilateral corneal sensation with recurrent ulcers and lid vesicles strongly suggests herpes simplex; confocal microscopy is particularly valuable in atypical presentations.<br><br>Corneal topography (A) maps curvature without diagnosing infection; conjunctival swab culture (B) has low yield for HSV; anterior segment OCT (C) assesses stromal depth not viral diagnosis; tear film osmolarity (D) assesses dry eye not herpetic disease.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient presents with severe ocular pain, photophobia, and a branching corneal epithelial lesion with terminal bulbs. Which diagnosis is most likely?","o":["Fungal keratitis","Marginal ulcer","Herpes simplex epithelial keratitis","Neurotrophic ulcer","Mooren ulcer"],"a":2,"e":"Herpes simplex epithelial keratitis classically presents with dendritic ulcers that branch and terminate in bulb-like endings visible with fluorescein staining.<br><br>Fungal keratitis (A) typically demonstrates feathery infiltrates and satellite lesions rather than dendritic epithelial branching.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A farmer develops corneal ulceration after trauma with sugarcane leaf. Slit lamp shows dry elevated infiltrate with feathery margins. Which organism type is most likely?","o":["Viral","Protozoal","Bacterial","Fungal","Chlamydial"],"a":3,"e":"Vegetative trauma strongly predisposes to filamentous fungal keratitis, especially caused by Aspergillus or Fusarium species.<br><br>Bacterial keratitis (C) usually produces dense suppurative infiltrates rather than dry feathery lesions.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal ulcer is strongly associated with contact lens misuse and ring infiltrates?","o":["Marginal keratitis","Herpetic keratitis","Mooren ulcer","Acanthamoeba keratitis","Neuroparalytic ulcer"],"a":3,"e":"Acanthamoeba keratitis commonly occurs in contact lens wearers and classically presents with severe pain and ring stromal infiltrates.<br><br>Herpetic keratitis (B) usually presents with dendritic epithelial ulcers rather than ring infiltrates.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which complication indicates impending corneal perforation in severe keratitis?","o":["Mild superficial punctate keratitis","Peripheral vascularization","Descemetocele formation","Arcus senilis","Band keratopathy"],"a":2,"e":"A descemetocele forms when stromal destruction leaves only Descemet membrane intact, indicating imminent perforation risk.<br><br>Urgent surgical management may be required to preserve globe integrity.<br><br>Band keratopathy (E) is a chronic calcium deposition disorder unrelated to acute perforation risk.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal ulcer is characteristically associated with reduced corneal sensation?","o":["Marginal ulcer","Mooren ulcer","Phlyctenular ulcer","Herpes simplex keratitis","Bacterial ulcer"],"a":3,"e":"Herpes simplex infection damages corneal sensory nerves and commonly produces reduced corneal sensation.<br><br>Assessment of corneal sensation is an important diagnostic clue in recurrent herpetic disease.<br><br>Bacterial ulcers (E) usually produce marked pain with preserved corneal sensation.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which investigation is most useful for rapid bedside diagnosis of fungal keratitis?","o":["Schirmer testing","KOH wet mount preparation","Gonioscopy","Automated perimetry","Amsler grid testing"],"a":1,"e":"KOH preparation rapidly dissolves epithelial debris while preserving fungal hyphae for microscopic visualization.<br><br>Gonioscopy (C) evaluates anterior chamber angles rather than infectious keratitis.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal ulcer is classically associated with severe pain disproportionate to slit-lamp findings?","o":["Neurotrophic ulcer","Marginal ulcer","Acanthamoeba keratitis","Exposure ulcer","Bullous keratopathy"],"a":2,"e":"Acanthamoeba keratitis produces intense pain because of radial keratoneuritis and deep stromal inflammation.<br><br>Neurotrophic ulcers (A) are usually relatively painless because of impaired corneal sensation.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which topical medication is contraindicated in active epithelial dendritic ulcer?","o":["Cycloplegic drops","Lubricating drops","Topical antibiotics","Topical corticosteroids","Oral acyclovir"],"a":3,"e":"Topical steroids promote viral replication in epithelial herpes simplex keratitis and may convert dendritic ulcers into large geographic ulcers.<br><br>Cycloplegics (A) may help relieve associated ciliary spasm and pain.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal ulcer is commonly associated with chronic blepharitis and hypersensitivity to staphylococcal antigens?","o":["Mooren ulcer","Neurotrophic ulcer","Fungal ulcer","Marginal ulcer","Herpetic ulcer"],"a":3,"e":"Marginal keratitis represents hypersensitivity reaction to staphylococcal antigens associated with chronic blepharitis.<br><br>The lesions are usually peripheral and separated from the limbus by a clear zone.<br><br>Mooren ulcer (A) is an autoimmune painful peripheral ulcerative keratitis rather than blepharitis-related hypersensitivity.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which organism is most strongly associated with rapidly progressive corneal melting in contact lens users?","o":["Candida albicans","Streptococcus pneumoniae","Pseudomonas aeruginosa","Herpes simplex virus","Corynebacterium diphtheriae"],"a":2,"e":"Pseudomonas produces proteolytic enzymes that rapidly destroy corneal stroma and may lead to perforation within a short time.<br><br>Candida (A) generally causes more indolent fungal keratitis rather than explosive corneal melting. Rapidly progressive Pseudomonas corneal melt in a lens wearer is a high-stakes emergency pattern.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal dystrophy is characterized by \"beaten metal\" appearance of the endothelium?","o":["Lattice dystrophy","Macular dystrophy","Granular dystrophy","Fuchs endothelial dystrophy","Reis-Bücklers dystrophy"],"a":3,"e":"Fuchs endothelial dystrophy is a progressive bilateral endothelial disorder characterized by corneal guttata producing a beaten-metal appearance on slit-lamp examination. It commonly affects elderly women and eventually causes stromal edema and painful epithelial bullae.<br><br>Morning blurring of vision is a classic symptom because endothelial pump failure causes overnight corneal hydration. Advanced disease may progress to bullous keratopathy with painful ruptured bullae.<br><br>Granular dystrophy (C) primarily affects the corneal stroma with breadcrumb-like opacities rather than endothelial guttata. Lattice dystrophy (A) produces branching stromal lines instead of beaten-metal endothelial changes.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal dystrophy classically presents with branching refractile stromal lines?","o":["Granular dystrophy","Lattice dystrophy","Macular dystrophy","Fuchs dystrophy","Band keratopathy"],"a":1,"e":"Lattice dystrophy is an autosomal dominant stromal dystrophy characterized by amyloid deposition forming branching refractile lattice lines within the corneal stroma. Patients may develop recurrent corneal erosions and progressive visual impairment later in life.<br><br>The dystrophy often begins in the first or second decade and gradually extends centrally, producing visual deterioration due to stromal haze and scarring.<br><br>Granular dystrophy (A) produces sharply demarcated breadcrumb-like stromal opacities rather than branching linear lesions. Band keratopathy (E) is a degeneration involving calcium deposition in superficial cornea.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal dystrophy is inherited as an autosomal recessive condition and involves the entire corneal stroma diffusely?","o":["Lattice dystrophy","Granular dystrophy","Macular dystrophy","Fuchs dystrophy","Posterior polymorphous dystrophy"],"a":2,"e":"Macular corneal dystrophy is an autosomal recessive stromal dystrophy characterized by diffuse stromal haze with poorly defined gray-white opacities extending to the limbus. It usually presents earlier than other stromal dystrophies.<br><br>Visual loss tends to be more severe because the entire corneal stroma becomes progressively clouded. Penetrating keratoplasty is often required at a younger age compared with lattice or granular dystrophy. Fuchs endothelial dystrophy with corneal guttata is a recurring slit-lamp recognition theme.<br><br>Granular dystrophy (B) is usually autosomal dominant and presents with discrete stromal deposits rather than diffuse haze. Fuchs dystrophy (D) primarily affects corneal endothelium instead of stroma.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient complains of recurrent painful episodes on awakening due to epithelial breakdown. Which dystrophy is most strongly associated with recurrent corneal erosions?","o":["Reis-Bücklers dystrophy","Fuchs dystrophy","Posterior polymorphous dystrophy","Arcus senilis","Vogt limbal girdle"],"a":0,"e":"Reis-Bücklers dystrophy affects Bowman layer and superficial cornea, producing recurrent painful epithelial erosions beginning early in life. Progressive superficial scarring may eventually reduce visual acuity.<br><br>Pain commonly occurs on awakening because the loosely adherent epithelium is disrupted during eyelid opening.<br><br>Arcus senilis (D) is a peripheral lipid degeneration usually unrelated to pain or epithelial breakdown. Posterior polymorphous dystrophy (C) mainly affects the endothelium and Descemet membrane.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal degeneration is commonly associated with aging and peripheral lipid deposition?","o":["Lattice dystrophy","Macular dystrophy","Arcus senilis","Keratoconus","Fuchs dystrophy"],"a":2,"e":"Arcus senilis is a common age-related corneal degeneration caused by peripheral stromal lipid deposition separated from the limbus by a lucid interval. It is usually bilateral and asymptomatic in elderly individuals.<br><br>The condition rarely affects vision because the central cornea remains clear. In younger individuals, however, arcus may suggest underlying hyperlipidemia and warrants systemic evaluation.<br><br>Keratoconus (D) is a noninflammatory ectatic disorder causing progressive corneal thinning and protrusion rather than peripheral lipid deposition. Lattice dystrophy (A) is an inherited stromal dystrophy.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal dystrophy is classically associated with breadcrumb-like stromal opacities?","o":["Granular dystrophy","Lattice dystrophy","Macular dystrophy","Fuchs dystrophy","Band keratopathy"],"a":0,"e":"Granular dystrophy is an autosomal dominant stromal dystrophy characterized by sharply demarcated white breadcrumb or snowflake-like stromal deposits. Visual acuity may remain relatively preserved initially.<br><br>The lesions enlarge and increase in number over time while intervening stromal tissue often remains clear during early disease. Recurrent erosions may occur in advanced stages.<br><br>Lattice dystrophy (B) presents with branching refractile lines caused by amyloid deposition rather than breadcrumb opacities. Macular dystrophy (C) causes diffuse stromal haze with indistinct lesions.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal degeneration is characterized by calcium deposition in Bowman layer?","o":["Band keratopathy","Arcus senilis","Fuchs dystrophy","Keratoglobus","Posterior polymorphous dystrophy"],"a":0,"e":"Band keratopathy results from calcium salt deposition in Bowman layer and superficial cornea, producing a horizontal gray-white opacity in the interpalpebral zone. It is associated with chronic ocular inflammation and hypercalcemia.<br><br>The calcific band often begins peripherally and progresses centrally, leaving small clear holes where corneal nerves pass. Chelation with EDTA may be used therapeutically.<br><br>Arcus senilis (B) represents peripheral stromal lipid deposition rather than calcium accumulation. Fuchs dystrophy (C) affects the corneal endothelium with guttata formation.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which clinical sign is classically associated with keratoconus?","o":["Guttata","Pterygium","Kayser-Fleischer ring","Munson sign","Bitot spot"],"a":3,"e":"Munson sign refers to V-shaped protrusion of the lower eyelid during downgaze caused by advanced keratoconus. Keratoconus is a progressive ectatic disorder with stromal thinning and irregular astigmatism.<br><br>Patients often present with progressive myopia, distorted vision, and intolerance to spectacles because of increasing irregular astigmatism. Slit-lamp findings may include Fleischer ring and Vogt striae.<br><br>Guttata (A) are endothelial excrescences seen in Fuchs dystrophy rather than keratoconus. Kayser-Fleischer ring (C) results from copper deposition in Wilson disease.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal dystrophy primarily affects the endothelium and Descemet membrane?","o":["Granular dystrophy","Lattice dystrophy","Macular dystrophy","Fuchs endothelial dystrophy","Reis-Bücklers dystrophy"],"a":3,"e":"Fuchs endothelial dystrophy involves progressive endothelial cell loss with Descemet membrane guttata formation. Endothelial pump failure eventually causes stromal and epithelial edema leading to visual impairment.<br><br>Patients commonly experience blurred morning vision because corneal edema worsens overnight. Advanced disease may produce painful epithelial bullae and bullous keratopathy.<br><br>Macular dystrophy (C) primarily affects corneal stroma diffusely rather than endothelium. Reis-Bücklers dystrophy (E) mainly involves Bowman layer with recurrent erosions.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal degeneration is commonly associated with chronic exposure to ultraviolet light and dust?","o":["Pterygium","Granular dystrophy","Macular dystrophy","Lattice dystrophy","Posterior polymorphous dystrophy"],"a":0,"e":"Pterygium is a fibrovascular degenerative growth of conjunctiva extending onto the cornea, strongly associated with ultraviolet exposure, dry climate, and chronic dust exposure. It commonly occurs nasally.<br><br>Patients may experience irritation, redness, cosmetic concerns, or visual impairment if the lesion encroaches upon the visual axis or induces astigmatism.<br><br>Granular dystrophy (B) is an inherited stromal dystrophy unrelated to environmental exposure. Posterior polymorphous dystrophy (E) is an endothelial dystrophy rather than conjunctival degeneration.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal dystrophy causes the greatest reduction in corneal sensation?","o":["Fuchs dystrophy","Lattice dystrophy","Herpes simplex keratitis","Granular dystrophy","Macular dystrophy"],"a":2,"e":"Herpes simplex keratitis commonly reduces corneal sensation because of viral involvement of trigeminal sensory nerves.<br><br>Recurrent disease may produce stromal scarring, neovascularization, and progressive visual impairment. Corneal anesthesia also predisposes to neurotrophic ulcer formation.<br><br>Lattice dystrophy (B) may cause recurrent erosions but does not typically produce marked corneal anesthesia. Fuchs dystrophy (A) primarily affects endothelial pump function rather than sensory innervation.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal dystrophy is inherited as an autosomal recessive disorder and causes diffuse stromal haze?","o":["Granular dystrophy","Lattice dystrophy","Macular dystrophy","Fuchs dystrophy","Reis-Bücklers dystrophy"],"a":2,"e":"Macular corneal dystrophy is an autosomal recessive stromal dystrophy characterized by diffuse stromal haze with indistinct gray-white opacities extending to the limbus. It often presents earlier than other stromal dystrophies.<br><br>Visual impairment is usually more severe because the entire corneal stroma progressively becomes clouded. Penetrating keratoplasty is commonly required at a relatively young age. Fuchs endothelial dystrophy with corneal guttata is a recurring slit-lamp recognition theme.<br><br>Granular dystrophy (A) is usually autosomal dominant and presents with sharply demarcated breadcrumb-like stromal deposits rather than diffuse haze. Fuchs dystrophy (D) primarily affects corneal endothelium.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which finding is most characteristic of advanced Fuchs endothelial dystrophy?","o":["Ring infiltrate","Bullous keratopathy","Dendritic ulcer","Satellite lesions","Hypopyon"],"a":1,"e":"Advanced Fuchs dystrophy causes endothelial pump failure resulting in stromal edema and epithelial bullae formation termed bullous keratopathy. Patients often experience painful ruptured bullae and blurred morning vision.<br><br>Corneal edema typically worsens overnight because evaporation is reduced during sleep. Progressive endothelial cell loss eventually leads to chronic visual impairment.<br><br>Dendritic ulcers (C) are characteristic of herpes simplex keratitis rather than endothelial dystrophy. Satellite lesions (D) strongly suggest fungal keratitis instead of corneal edema syndromes.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal degeneration is strongly associated with peripheral thinning and superficial vascularization?","o":["Terrien marginal degeneration","Granular dystrophy","Macular dystrophy","Fuchs dystrophy","Lattice dystrophy"],"a":0,"e":"Terrien marginal degeneration is a peripheral corneal thinning disorder associated with superficial vascularization and lipid deposition. The epithelium generally remains intact despite marked stromal thinning.<br><br>Patients commonly develop high against-the-rule astigmatism because of peripheral corneal distortion. Rarely, spontaneous perforation may occur in advanced disease. Fuchs endothelial dystrophy with corneal guttata is a recurring slit-lamp recognition theme.<br><br>Granular dystrophy (B) is a hereditary stromal dystrophy without peripheral thinning. Fuchs dystrophy (D) primarily affects the corneal endothelium rather than peripheral stroma.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal dystrophy is inherited most commonly as an autosomal dominant disorder with breadcrumb-like opacities?","o":["Macular dystrophy","Granular dystrophy","Posterior crocodile shagreen","Arcus senilis","Band keratopathy"],"a":1,"e":"Granular dystrophy is an autosomal dominant stromal dystrophy characterized by sharply demarcated white breadcrumb or snowflake-like stromal deposits. Vision may initially remain preserved because intervening stroma stays relatively clear.<br><br>The deposits gradually enlarge and increase in number with age, eventually causing visual deterioration and recurrent erosions in some patients.<br><br>Macular dystrophy (A) is autosomal recessive and produces diffuse stromal haze rather than discrete stromal opacities. Posterior crocodile shagreen (C) is a degeneration rather than hereditary dystrophy.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal ectatic disorder is characterized by progressive stromal thinning and conical protrusion?","o":["Fuchs dystrophy","Arcus senilis","Band keratopathy","Keratoconus","Reis-Bücklers dystrophy"],"a":3,"e":"Keratoconus is a progressive noninflammatory ectatic disorder causing central or paracentral stromal thinning with conical corneal protrusion and irregular astigmatism.<br><br>Patients typically present with progressive myopia, distorted vision, and increasing intolerance to spectacles because of irregular astigmatism.<br><br>Band keratopathy (C) involves calcium deposition in superficial cornea rather than stromal thinning. Reis-Bücklers dystrophy (E) primarily affects Bowman layer with recurrent erosions.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which slit-lamp sign is classically associated with keratoconus?","o":["Guttata","Fleischer ring","Dendritic ulcer","Keratic precipitates","Hypopyon"],"a":1,"e":"Fleischer ring is an iron deposition ring around the base of the corneal cone in keratoconus and is best visualized using cobalt-blue illumination. It is a classic diagnostic sign.<br><br>Other important keratoconus signs include Vogt striae, Munson sign, and progressive irregular astigmatism causing visual distortion.<br><br>Guttata (A) are endothelial excrescences characteristic of Fuchs dystrophy rather than keratoconus. Keratic precipitates (D) are associated with anterior uveitis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal degeneration appears as polygonal posterior stromal opacities in elderly individuals?","o":["Posterior crocodile shagreen","Granular dystrophy","Lattice dystrophy","Macular dystrophy","Reis-Bücklers dystrophy"],"a":0,"e":"Posterior crocodile shagreen is a benign age-related stromal degeneration characterized by polygonal gray-white posterior stromal opacities resembling crocodile skin. It is usually asymptomatic.<br><br>The degeneration is often discovered incidentally during slit-lamp examination and rarely affects visual acuity significantly. No treatment is generally required.<br><br>Lattice dystrophy (C) produces branching refractile stromal lines rather than polygonal stromal patterns. Reis-Bücklers dystrophy (E) causes recurrent erosions and superficial scarring.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal dystrophy is most commonly associated with recurrent painful corneal erosions?","o":["Reis-Bücklers dystrophy","Fuchs dystrophy","Posterior polymorphous dystrophy","Arcus senilis","Vogt limbal girdle"],"a":0,"e":"Reis-Bücklers dystrophy affects Bowman layer and superficial stroma, producing recurrent epithelial breakdown and painful corneal erosions from childhood or adolescence onward.<br><br>Repeated erosions lead to superficial scarring and gradual visual deterioration. Symptoms are often worse upon awakening because the epithelium adheres to the eyelid overnight.<br><br>Arcus senilis (D) is a painless peripheral degeneration without epithelial instability. Posterior polymorphous dystrophy (C) mainly affects Descemet membrane and endothelium.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which degeneration is characterized by peripheral conjunctival fibrovascular growth extending onto the cornea?","o":["Pterygium","Arcus senilis","Band keratopathy","Lattice dystrophy","Granular dystrophy"],"a":0,"e":"Pterygium is a fibrovascular degenerative growth of bulbar conjunctiva extending onto the cornea, strongly associated with ultraviolet light exposure, dry climate, and dust.<br><br>The lesion usually arises nasally within the interpalpebral fissure and may induce astigmatism or obscure the visual axis in advanced cases.<br><br>Arcus senilis (B) represents peripheral lipid deposition rather than fibrovascular conjunctival growth. Granular dystrophy (E) is a hereditary stromal dystrophy.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal dystrophy primarily involves Descemet membrane and corneal endothelium with vesicular lesions?","o":["Granular dystrophy","Macular dystrophy","Lattice dystrophy","Posterior polymorphous dystrophy","Keratoglobus"],"a":3,"e":"Posterior polymorphous dystrophy is an endothelial and Descemet membrane dystrophy characterized by vesicular, band-like, or geographic lesions on the posterior corneal surface.<br><br>Most patients remain asymptomatic, although some may develop corneal edema or secondary glaucoma because of abnormal endothelial cell proliferation.<br><br>Granular dystrophy (A) and lattice dystrophy (C) are stromal dystrophies rather than endothelial disorders. Keratoglobus (E) is a generalized ectatic thinning disorder.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 45-year-old woman presents with progressive painful attacks of blurring on waking that improve during the day. Slit-lamp shows epithelial microcysts and map-dot-fingerprint changes. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Epithelial basement membrane dystrophy","Meesmann dystrophy","Reis-Bucklers dystrophy","Thiel-Behnke dystrophy","Macular dystrophy"],"a":0,"e":"Epithelial basement membrane dystrophy causes recurrent corneal erosions characteristically worse on waking; the slit-lamp findings of map, dot, and fingerprint patterns result from abnormal basement membrane proliferating into the epithelium trapping cells and producing microcysts.<br><br>Symptoms improve during the day as the epithelium re-adheres with blinking; treatment includes hypertonic saline drops, bandage contact lens, and anterior stromal puncture for recalcitrant cases.<br><br>Meesmann dystrophy (B) shows tiny intraepithelial vesicles in childhood; Reis-Bucklers (C) affects Bowman layer with recurrent erosions and subepithelial scarring; Thiel-Behnke (D) shows honeycomb Bowman layer opacities; macular dystrophy (E) is a stromal condition.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 10-year-old child is found on slit-lamp examination to have tiny intraepithelial vesicles distributed across both corneas in a band-shaped pattern. Vision is minimally affected. Family history is positive. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Lattice dystrophy type one","Macular corneal dystrophy","Granular dystrophy type one","Meesmann epithelial dystrophy","Fuchs"],"a":3,"e":"Meesmann dystrophy is an autosomal dominant condition caused by KRT3 or KRT12 mutations affecting corneal keratin; it presents in early childhood with innumerable tiny intraepithelial vesicles distributed uniformly across the cornea, best seen on retroillumination.<br><br>Vision is relatively preserved until vesicles rupture causing recurrent erosions in adulthood; the condition is slowly progressive with minimal treatment required in most cases beyond lubricating drops.<br><br>Lattice dystrophy (A) shows branching lines in the stroma not intraepithelial vesicles; granular dystrophy (C) shows discrete white stromal deposits; macular dystrophy (B) causes diffuse stromal clouding; Fuchs dystrophy (E) affects the endothelium not the epithelium.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 25-year-old presents with recurrent painful corneal erosions and progressive subepithelial opacification reducing vision. Slit-lamp shows grey-white irregular Bowman layer opacities replacing normal architecture. Histology shows fibrocellular tissue replacing Bowman layer. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Thiel-Behnke dystrophy","Meesmann dystrophy","Reis-Bucklers dystrophy","Macular dystrophy","Granular dystrophy"],"a":2,"e":"Reis-Bucklers dystrophy is an autosomal dominant TGFBI mutation causing progressive replacement of Bowman layer with fibrocellular tissue; it presents in the first decade with recurrent erosions and progressive irregular grey-white subepithelial opacification reducing vision significantly by adulthood.<br><br>Histology classically shows replacement of Bowman layer with fibrocellular connective tissue staining with Masson trichrome; treatment is phototherapeutic keratectomy or penetrating keratoplasty for advanced cases. This stromal dystrophy with its characteristic deposits is a recurring morphology question.<br><br>Thiel-Behnke dystrophy (A) shows honeycomb Bowman opacities with curly collagen fibres on electron microscopy; Meesmann (B) causes intraepithelial vesicles; macular dystrophy (D) affects the stroma; granular dystrophy (E) shows discrete hyaline deposits in clear stroma.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 30-year-old presents with discrete white crumb-like deposits in the central anterior stroma with clear intervening cornea and peripheral sparing. Vision is mildly reduced. Histology shows hyaline deposits staining with Masson trichrome. What is the most likely diagnosis?","o":["Macular dystrophy","Lattice dystrophy","Fuchs dystrophy","Granular dystrophy type one","Schnyder dystrophy"],"a":3,"e":"Granular dystrophy type one is caused by TGFBI mutations producing discrete hyaline deposits in the central anterior stroma with clear intervening cornea and peripheral sparing; the deposits stain bright red with Masson trichrome distinguishing them from other stromal dystrophies.<br><br>Vision remains relatively preserved until deposits coalesce in later decades; phototherapeutic keratectomy removes superficial deposits effectively though recurrence in the graft occurs after penetrating keratoplasty. Fuchs endothelial dystrophy with corneal guttata is a recurring slit-lamp recognition theme.<br><br>Macular dystrophy (A) causes diffuse clouding without clear intervening stroma; lattice dystrophy (B) shows amyloid branching lines; Fuchs dystrophy (C) affects the endothelium; Schnyder dystrophy (E) shows central crystalline stromal deposits with arcus.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 20-year-old presents with lattice lines visible as branching refractile lines in the anterior stroma. He has recurrent painful corneal erosions. Histology shows amyloid deposits staining with Congo red showing apple-green birefringence under polarised light. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Granular dystrophy","Macular dystrophy","Schnyder dystrophy","Avellino dystrophy","Lattice corneal dystrophy type one"],"a":4,"e":"Lattice dystrophy type one is caused by TGFBI mutations producing amyloid deposition in the corneal stroma; the branching refractile lines represent amyloid deposits and confirm the diagnosis when histology shows Congo red positivity with apple-green birefringence under polarised light.<br><br>Recurrent erosions occur as amyloid disrupts epithelial adhesion; vision deteriorates as deposits coalesce; treatment is phototherapeutic keratectomy for erosions and penetrating keratoplasty for advanced visual loss. This stromal dystrophy with its characteristic deposits is a recurring morphology question.<br><br>Granular dystrophy (A) shows hyaline deposits staining with Masson trichrome; macular dystrophy (B) shows glycosaminoglycan deposits; Schnyder dystrophy (C) shows cholesterol crystals; Avellino dystrophy (D) shows both granular and lattice features combined.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 35-year-old presents with diffuse stromal clouding extending from limbus to limbus including the peripheral cornea. Central corneal thickness is reduced. Histology shows glycosaminoglycan deposits staining with Alcian blue. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Macular corneal dystrophy","Granular dystrophy","Lattice dystrophy","Schnyder dystrophy","Fuchs dystrophy"],"a":0,"e":"Macular corneal dystrophy is caused by CHST6 mutations causing defective keratan sulphate sulphation; glycosaminoglycan accumulation produces diffuse stromal clouding without clear intervening areas, extending to the limbus and thinning the central cornea, distinguishing it from granular and lattice dystrophies.<br><br>It is autosomal recessive unlike most corneal dystrophies; histology shows Alcian blue and colloidal iron positive deposits within keratocytes and extracellularly; penetrating keratoplasty provides good results though recurrence can occur. Fuchs endothelial dystrophy with corneal guttata is a recurring slit-lamp recognition theme.<br><br>Granular dystrophy (B) shows discrete deposits with clear intervening stroma; lattice dystrophy (C) shows amyloid branching lines; Schnyder dystrophy (D) shows cholesterol crystals centrally; Fuchs dystrophy (E) affects the endothelium not stroma.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 40-year-old with hypercholesterolaemia presents with a central disc-shaped corneal opacity with polychromatic crystalline deposits and a dense arcus. Histology shows cholesterol and lipid deposits in the stroma. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Macular dystrophy","Schnyder corneal dystrophy","Granular dystrophy","Lattice dystrophy","Fleck dystrophy"],"a":1,"e":"Schnyder corneal dystrophy is caused by UBIAD1 mutations causing abnormal cholesterol metabolism; it presents with central disc-shaped crystalline stromal deposits, dense arcus juvenilis, and corneal haze; systemic hypercholesterolaemia is present in over half of affected patients.<br><br>Histology reveals cholesterol and phospholipid deposits within the stroma; vision deteriorates as haze progresses; phototherapeutic keratectomy and penetrating keratoplasty are surgical options for visually significant disease. This stromal dystrophy with its characteristic deposits is a recurring morphology question.<br><br>Macular dystrophy (A) causes diffuse glycosaminoglycan clouding; granular dystrophy (C) shows hyaline deposits with clear intervening stroma; lattice dystrophy (D) shows amyloid branching lines; fleck dystrophy (E) shows diffuse dandruff-like deposits across the entire stroma.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 50-year-old woman presents with decreased vision and glare worse in bright light. Slit-lamp shows beaten-bronze appearance of the corneal endothelium with guttae. Specular microscopy shows reduced endothelial cell count. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Posterior polymorphous dystrophy","Congenital hereditary endothelial dystrophy","Fuchs endothelial corneal dystrophy","Macular dystrophy","Iridocorneal endothelial syndrome"],"a":2,"e":"Fuchs endothelial corneal dystrophy is caused by SLC4A11 or TCF4 mutations; guttae representing focal thickening of Descemet membrane with overlying endothelial cell loss produce the beaten-bronze appearance; decompensation causes stromal and epithelial oedema with glare and halos.<br><br>It is more common in females and inherited as autosomal dominant; Descemet membrane endothelial keratoplasty has replaced penetrating keratoplasty as the surgical treatment of choice for advanced decompensation. Fuchs endothelial dystrophy with corneal guttata is a recurring slit-lamp recognition theme.<br><br>Posterior polymorphous dystrophy (A) shows vesicular or band endothelial lesions; congenital hereditary endothelial dystrophy (B) presents at birth; macular dystrophy (D) is a stromal condition; iridocorneal endothelial syndrome (E) is non-hereditary and unilateral.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 60-year-old male with Fuchs endothelial dystrophy develops bullous keratopathy. He reports worse vision on waking gradually improving through the morning. What is the explanation for this pattern?","o":["Increased tear production overnight","Corneal hydration increases during sleep from reduced evaporation","Nocturnal IOP elevation worsening oedema","Reduced corneal hydration during sleep worsening oedema","Diurnal ciliary muscle variation affecting corneal curvature"],"a":3,"e":"In Fuchs dystrophy, the decompensated endothelium cannot maintain corneal dehydration; during sleep lid closure reduces evaporative fluid loss from the corneal surface, allowing oedema to worsen; this explains vision being worst on waking, improving as evaporation increases with eye opening.<br><br>Hypertonic saline drops and a hairdryer held at arm's length accelerate evaporation providing symptomatic morning relief; definitive treatment is Descemet membrane endothelial keratoplasty replacing the diseased endothelium. Fuchs endothelial dystrophy with corneal guttata is a recurring slit-lamp recognition theme.<br><br>Increased tear production overnight (A) does not occur; corneal hydration increasing during sleep (B) is the mechanism but the wording is reversed; nocturnal IOP elevation (C) is not the primary mechanism; ciliary muscle variation (E) does not affect corneal hydration.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A neonate is found to have bilateral diffuse corneal clouding present from birth. The cornea appears ground-glass white. Intraocular pressure is normal. There is no family history. What is the most likely diagnosis?","o":["Congenital glaucoma","Mucopolysaccharidosis","Peters anomaly","Posterior polymorphous dystrophy","Congenital hereditary endothelial"],"a":4,"e":"Congenital hereditary endothelial dystrophy presents at birth with bilateral diffuse ground-glass corneal clouding from primary endothelial failure; the absence of raised IOP excludes congenital glaucoma which is the critical differential diagnosis in a cloudy neonatal cornea.<br><br>The autosomal recessive form presents at birth while the dominant form develops in early childhood; treatment requires early penetrating keratoplasty to prevent stimulus deprivation amblyopia during the critical period of visual development.<br><br>Congenital glaucoma (A) causes clouding from raised IOP with buphthalmos; mucopolysaccharidosis (B) causes clouding from stromal deposits appearing later; Peters anomaly (C) has a central opacity with posterior corneal defect; posterior polymorphous dystrophy (D) is usually mild and detected later.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 25-year-old presents with progressive irregular astigmatism and myopia. Retinoscopy shows a scissor reflex. Slit-lamp shows inferior corneal thinning and steepening with Vogt striae and Fleischer ring. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Keratoconus","Pellucid marginal degeneration","Keratoglobus","Terrien marginal degeneration","Mooren ulcer"],"a":0,"e":"Keratoconus is the most common corneal ectasia; the combination of progressive myopia, irregular astigmatism, scissor reflex on retinoscopy, Vogt striae from stromal stress, Fleischer ring from iron deposition at the base of the cone, and inferior corneal thinning are pathognomonic.<br><br>Corneal collagen crosslinking halts progression; rigid gas permeable lenses optimise vision; Intacs segments flatten the cone; penetrating or deep anterior lamellar keratoplasty is reserved for contact lens intolerance or advanced disease. This ectatic corneal disorder with its classic signs is a heavily emphasised examination favourite.<br><br>Pellucid marginal degeneration (B) causes inferior peripheral thinning with against-the-rule astigmatism and no Fleischer ring; keratoglobus (C) causes global corneal thinning; Terrien degeneration (D) is peripheral and non-ectatic; Mooren ulcer (E) is a peripheral ulcerative condition.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A Fleischer ring at the base of the cone in keratoconus is composed of which substance?","o":["Calcium deposits","Iron within basal epithelial cells","Amyloid deposits","Copper deposits","Lipid deposits"],"a":1,"e":"The Fleischer ring in keratoconus is formed by haemosiderin iron deposition within the basal epithelial cells at the base of the cone; it appears as a partial or complete yellowish-brown ring best seen with cobalt blue filter and is pathognomonic of keratoconus.<br><br>Similar iron lines occur at other corneal irregularities; the Ferry line forms anterior to filtering blebs and the Stocker line forms at the leading edge of pterygia; all represent iron deposition in areas of tear film pooling.<br><br>Calcium deposits (A) cause band keratopathy; amyloid (C) deposits in lattice dystrophy; copper deposits (D) form the Kayser-Fleischer ring in Wilson disease at Descemet membrane level; lipid deposits (E) cause corneal arcus.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 30-year-old presents with inferior peripheral corneal thinning with the thinnest point 1 to 2 mm from the limbus. The thinning extends circumferentially. Corneal topography shows against-the-rule astigmatism with superior steepening. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Keratoconus","Keratoglobus","Pellucid marginal degeneration","Terrien marginal degeneration","Mooren ulcer"],"a":2,"e":"Pellucid marginal degeneration causes inferior peripheral corneal thinning 1 to 2 mm from the limbus; the thinned zone is clear and non-vascularised; the characteristic crab-claw or butterfly topographic pattern with against-the-rule astigmatism from superior corneal steepening is pathognomonic.<br><br>Unlike keratoconus there is no Fleischer ring or Vogt striae; the management is rigid gas permeable contact lenses; large diameter deep anterior lamellar or penetrating keratoplasty is required for intolerance cases. This ectatic corneal disorder with its classic signs is a heavily emphasised examination favourite.<br><br>Keratoconus (A) causes central or paracentral thinning with Fleischer ring; keratoglobus (B) causes global thinning affecting the entire cornea; Terrien degeneration (D) is superior peripheral and associated with vascularisation; Mooren ulcer (E) is painful and progressive.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 20-year-old with Down syndrome presents with bilateral progressive corneal thinning affecting the entire cornea producing a globular appearance. The cornea is uniformly thin to 20% of normal thickness. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Keratoconus","Pellucid marginal degeneration","Terrien marginal degeneration","Keratoglobus","Corneal ectasia"],"a":3,"e":"Keratoglobus is a rare bilateral ectasia causing generalised thinning of the entire cornea to as little as one-fifth of normal thickness with a globular configuration; it is associated with Down syndrome, Leber congenital amaurosis, and connective tissue disorders including Ehlers-Danlos syndrome.<br><br>Unlike keratoconus which causes focal inferior thinning, the entire cornea is affected; the extreme thinning carries a high risk of corneal perforation from minor trauma; large diameter penetrating keratoplasty is technically challenging. This ectatic corneal disorder with its classic signs is a heavily emphasised examination favourite.<br><br>Keratoconus (A) causes focal central or inferior thinning not global; pellucid (B) causes inferior peripheral thinning; Terrien degeneration (C) is superior peripheral; corneal ectasia (E) is a post-refractive surgery complication not a primary bilateral condition.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 70-year-old presents with a white peripheral corneal opacity beginning superiorly, associated with superficial vascularisation and slow circumferential progression over many years. There is no pain. The opacity has a lucid interval separating it from the limbus. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Mooren ulcer","Peripheral ulcerative keratitis","Marginal keratitis","Fuchs superficial marginal keratitis","Terrien marginal degeneration"],"a":4,"e":"Terrien marginal degeneration is a non-inflammatory peripheral corneal thinning beginning superiorly with a characteristic leading edge of lipid deposits, superficial vascularisation, and a lucid interval between the opacity and limbus; it is painless and slowly progressive distinguishing it from inflammatory peripheral conditions.<br><br>Against-the-rule astigmatism develops as the superior cornea thins and flattens; corneal perforation can occur spontaneously or following minor trauma; large eccentric lamellar or penetrating keratoplasty is required for thinning at risk of perforation. Fuchs endothelial dystrophy with corneal guttata is a recurring slit-lamp recognition theme.<br><br>Mooren ulcer (A) is painful with undermined edges; peripheral ulcerative keratitis (B) is associated with systemic vasculitis; marginal keratitis (C) is associated with blepharitis; Fuchs superficial marginal keratitis (D) is associated with staphylococcal disease not peripheral thinning.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 65-year-old presents with a white band-shaped opacity across the interpalpebral zone of the cornea in a horizontal band. The opacity has clear holes within it and begins at the peripheral cornea. Calcium deposits are confirmed on histology. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Band keratopathy","Arcus senilis","Salzmann nodular degeneration","Lipid keratopathy","Corneal farinata"],"a":0,"e":"Band keratopathy results from calcium phosphate deposition in Bowman layer and superficial stroma in the interpalpebral zone; the Swiss-cheese holes within the band represent corneal nerves penetrating Bowman layer; it occurs in chronic uveitis, hypercalcaemia, hyperphosphataemia, and chronic corneal disease.<br><br>Treatment is EDTA chelation under topical anaesthesia which dissolves calcium deposits; phototherapeutic keratectomy removes residual opacity; treating the underlying cause prevents recurrence.<br><br>Arcus senilis (B) is a peripheral lipid deposition with a clear lucid interval; Salzmann nodular degeneration (C) causes elevated grey-white nodules; lipid keratopathy (D) causes stromal lipid deposits following vascularisation; corneal farinata (E) causes deep stromal dust-like deposits.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 55-year-old patient with longstanding dry eye and previous phlyctenular keratitis presents with elevated grey-white nodules on the anterior corneal surface. The nodules are subepithelial. Vision is reduced. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Salzmann nodular degeneration","Band keratopathy","Lipid keratopathy","Corneal keloid","Spheroidal degeneration"],"a":0,"e":"Salzmann nodular degeneration causes elevated grey-white avascular subepithelial nodules typically following chronic corneal inflammation from conditions including phlyctenular keratitis, trachoma, and interstitial keratitis; the nodules replace Bowman layer with hyaline fibrous tissue.<br><br>Superficial keratectomy removes nodules restoring vision; phototherapeutic keratectomy is an effective alternative; the condition may recur particularly in eyes with persistent ocular surface inflammation as the underlying trigger.<br><br>Band keratopathy (B) forms a horizontal interpalpebral band not discrete nodules; lipid keratopathy (C) causes stromal lipid infiltration with vascularisation; corneal keloid (D) is a rare raised scar; spheroidal degeneration (E) causes amber-coloured droplets not elevated nodules.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 70-year-old patient presents with a creamy-white peripheral corneal opacity forming a complete ring. There is a clear lucid interval between the opacity and the limbus. The patient has no visual symptoms. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Band keratopathy","Salzmann degeneration","Arcus senilis","Lipid keratopathy","Terrien degeneration"],"a":2,"e":"Arcus senilis is a bilateral peripheral corneal lipid deposition forming a grey-white ring in the peripheral stroma; it is separated from the limbus by a clear lucid interval; it is a normal ageing change in patients over 60 years and requires no treatment.<br><br>In patients under 40 years the condition is called arcus juvenilis and warrants systemic investigation for hypercholesterolaemia and hyperlipoproteinaemia as it may indicate premature cardiovascular disease risk.<br><br>Band keratopathy (A) forms a horizontal interpalpebral band with calcium deposits; Salzmann degeneration (B) causes elevated nodules; lipid keratopathy (D) causes irregular stromal deposits following vascularisation; Terrien degeneration (E) causes peripheral thinning with vascularisation.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 40-year-old presents with a pterygium encroaching onto the cornea from the nasal limbus. An iron line is visible at its advancing edge. What is this iron line called?","o":["Fleischer ring","Ferry line","Hudson-Stahli line","Stocker line","Kayser-Fleischer ring"],"a":3,"e":"The Stocker line is an iron deposit in the basal corneal epithelium at the advancing head of a pterygium; like other corneal iron lines it forms where tear film pools; its presence indicates a slow-growing pterygium as faster-growing pterygia do not allow time for iron accumulation.<br><br>Iron lines at other sites include the Fleischer ring at the keratoconus cone base, the Ferry line anterior to filtering blebs, and the Hudson-Stahli line at the junction of the upper two-thirds and lower one-third of the cornea in normal ageing.<br><br>Fleischer ring (A) is at the keratoconus cone base; Ferry line (B) is anterior to filtering blebs; Hudson-Stahli line (C) is a horizontal line in normal ageing; Kayser-Fleischer ring (E) is copper deposition in Wilson disease at Descemet membrane.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 35-year-old farmer from a sunny climate presents with bilateral fleshy triangular vascular tissue growing from the nasal conjunctiva onto the cornea. It is causing induced astigmatism. What is the most important surgical concern during pterygium excision?","o":["Risk of endophthalmitis","Risk of macular oedema","Risk of cataract formation","Risk of recurrence requiring adjunctive measures","Risk of"],"a":3,"e":"Pterygium recurrence after bare sclera excision alone reaches 80%; conjunctival autograft transplantation from the superior bulbar conjunctiva is the gold standard reducing recurrence to under 10%; intraoperative mitomycin C or postoperative beta irradiation are adjunctive options for high-risk cases.<br><br>UV radiation and outdoor exposure are the primary risk factors; the induced astigmatism from corneal traction resolves after excision though some residual topographic change may persist if the pterygium was large and longstanding.<br><br>Endophthalmitis (A) is a rare postoperative infection not the primary surgical concern; macular oedema (B) does not occur with pterygium surgery; cataract formation (C) is not a recognised complication; vitreous loss (E) is irrelevant as pterygium surgery is entirely anterior.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal ectatic disorder is characterized by progressive noninflammatory central corneal thinning with conical protrusion?","o":["Keratoglobus","Pellucid marginal degeneration","Keratoconus","Terrien marginal degeneration","Posterior keratoconus"],"a":2,"e":"Keratoconus is a progressive noninflammatory ectatic disorder causing central or paracentral stromal thinning with conical protrusion of the cornea. Patients commonly develop irregular astigmatism and progressive myopia.<br><br>The disease usually presents during adolescence or early adulthood and progresses variably over time. Slit-lamp findings include Fleischer ring, Vogt striae, and Munson sign in advanced disease.<br><br>Keratoglobus (A) causes diffuse generalized thinning rather than localized conical protrusion. Pellucid marginal degeneration (B) primarily affects the inferior peripheral cornea.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which slit-lamp sign is classically associated with keratoconus?","o":["Guttata","Vogt striae","Dendritic ulcer","Hypopyon","Keratic precipitates"],"a":1,"e":"Vogt striae are fine vertical stress lines seen in the deep stroma and Descemet membrane in keratoconus. They disappear temporarily with gentle pressure on the globe.<br><br>These lines result from mechanical stretching of the thinned ectatic cornea and are highly characteristic of keratoconus. Fleischer ring and Munson sign are additional classic findings.<br><br>Guttata (A) are endothelial excrescences associated with Fuchs dystrophy rather than ectatic disease. Dendritic ulcers (C) are typical of herpes simplex keratitis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal ectasia is characterized by diffuse limbus-to-limbus thinning?","o":["Keratoconus","Pellucid marginal degeneration","Terrien marginal degeneration","Keratoglobus","Posterior keratoconus"],"a":3,"e":"Keratoglobus is a rare ectatic disorder characterized by generalized limbus-to-limbus corneal thinning with globular protrusion of the cornea. The cornea becomes extremely fragile.<br><br>Patients are at high risk of corneal rupture even after minor trauma because of marked diffuse stromal thinning. Visual impairment results mainly from irregular astigmatism.<br><br>Keratoconus (A) typically causes localized central or paracentral thinning rather than diffuse generalized ectasia. Pellucid degeneration (B) mainly affects the inferior peripheral cornea.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which clinical sign is seen in advanced keratoconus when the patient looks downward?","o":["Bitot spot","Hutchinson sign","Arlt triangle","Munson sign","Marcus Gunn pupil"],"a":3,"e":"Munson sign refers to V-shaped protrusion of the lower eyelid during downgaze caused by advanced conical protrusion of the cornea in keratoconus.<br><br>It is a classic late clinical sign and indicates advanced ectatic disease with significant stromal thinning and protrusion.<br><br>Marcus Gunn pupil (E) is associated with optic nerve disease rather than corneal ectasia. Bitot spots (A) occur in vitamin A deficiency.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which ectatic disorder classically produces \"kissing birds\" or \"crab-claw\" topography pattern?","o":["Keratoconus","Posterior keratoconus","Keratoglobus","Pellucid marginal degeneration","Terrien marginal degeneration"],"a":3,"e":"Pellucid marginal degeneration is characterized by inferior peripheral corneal thinning with protrusion occurring just above the thinned area. Corneal topography classically shows a crab-claw or kissing-birds appearance.<br><br>Patients commonly develop high against-the-rule astigmatism and visual distortion. The ectasia is usually bilateral but asymmetric.<br><br>Keratoconus (A) produces central or paracentral cone formation rather than peripheral inferior thinning with crab-claw topography.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which ring is caused by iron deposition around the base of the cone in keratoconus?","o":["Kayser-Fleischer ring","Fleischer ring","Wessely ring","Coats ring","Weiss ring"],"a":1,"e":"Fleischer ring is an iron deposition ring around the base of the corneal cone in keratoconus and is best visualized using cobalt-blue illumination.<br><br>It develops because altered tear film dynamics lead to iron accumulation within basal epithelial cells surrounding the ectatic area.<br><br>Kayser-Fleischer ring (A) is caused by copper deposition in Wilson disease. Weiss ring (E) is associated with posterior vitreous detachment rather than corneal disease.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal ectasia is most commonly associated with Down syndrome and eye rubbing?","o":["Keratoglobus","Pellucid marginal degeneration","Keratoconus","Posterior keratoconus","Terrien marginal degeneration"],"a":2,"e":"Keratoconus is strongly associated with Down syndrome, atopy, vernal keratoconjunctivitis, and chronic vigorous eye rubbing. These factors contribute to progressive stromal weakening.<br><br>Patients typically develop increasing irregular astigmatism and progressive visual distortion during adolescence or early adulthood.<br><br>Terrien marginal degeneration (E) is a peripheral thinning disorder unrelated to Down syndrome or chronic eye rubbing.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which ectatic disorder primarily affects the inferior peripheral cornea?","o":["Keratoglobus","Keratoconus","Posterior keratoconus","Pellucid marginal degeneration","Fuchs dystrophy"],"a":3,"e":"Pellucid marginal degeneration causes a narrow band of inferior peripheral stromal thinning, usually located between the 4 and 8 o'clock positions.<br><br>The area of maximal protrusion lies just superior to the thinning, producing marked irregular against-the-rule astigmatism and distorted vision.<br><br>Keratoglobus (A) produces diffuse limbus-to-limbus thinning rather than localized inferior peripheral ectasia. Fuchs dystrophy (E) is an endothelial dystrophy.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which investigation is most sensitive for early detection of keratoconus?","o":["Schirmer testing","Gonioscopy","Corneal topography","Visual field testing","Fluorescein angiography"],"a":2,"e":"Corneal topography is highly sensitive for detecting early keratoconus and demonstrates characteristic asymmetric inferior steepening before slit-lamp changes become obvious.<br><br>Modern tomography techniques can identify subclinical ectasia and are essential before refractive surgery screening.<br><br>Visual field testing (D) evaluates optic nerve function rather than corneal curvature abnormalities. Gonioscopy (B) assesses anterior chamber angles.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which treatment halts progression of keratoconus by strengthening stromal collagen bonds?","o":["Penetrating keratoplasty","Photorefractive keratectomy","Radial keratotomy","Corneal collagen cross-linking","Cyclophotocoagulation"],"a":3,"e":"Corneal collagen cross-linking uses riboflavin and ultraviolet-A light to strengthen stromal collagen fibrils and halt progression of keratoconus.<br><br>It is particularly effective in progressive ectasia and may reduce the future need for corneal transplantation.<br><br>Penetrating keratoplasty (A) replaces diseased cornea but does not specifically stabilize ectatic progression in early disease. Radial keratotomy (C) may worsen ectasia.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal ectasia may develop after LASIK surgery?","o":["Band keratopathy","Post-LASIK ectasia","Arcus senilis","Reis-Bücklers dystrophy","Pterygium"],"a":1,"e":"Post-LASIK ectasia is a progressive corneal thinning disorder occurring after refractive surgery due to biomechanical weakening of the corneal stroma.<br><br>Risk factors include preexisting forme fruste keratoconus, thin corneas, and excessive stromal tissue removal.<br><br>Arcus senilis (C) is a lipid degeneration unrelated to refractive surgery. Pterygium (E) is a conjunctival degeneration associated with ultraviolet exposure.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which ectatic disorder typically causes high irregular astigmatism with scissoring reflex on retinoscopy?","o":["Keratoconus","Fuchs dystrophy","Band keratopathy","Arcus senilis","Posterior polymorphous dystrophy"],"a":0,"e":"Keratoconus produces progressive irregular astigmatism leading to a characteristic scissoring reflex on retinoscopy because of distorted corneal curvature.<br><br>Patients often experience ghost images, monocular diplopia, and frequent spectacle prescription changes.<br><br>Fuchs dystrophy (B) causes corneal edema from endothelial dysfunction rather than irregular ectatic astigmatism. Arcus senilis (D) usually does not affect vision significantly.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal ectasia is usually noninflammatory despite marked stromal thinning?","o":["Mooren ulcer","Marginal keratitis","Peripheral ulcerative keratitis","Keratoconus","Interstitial keratitis"],"a":3,"e":"Keratoconus is considered a noninflammatory ectatic disorder despite progressive stromal thinning and protrusion. Histologically, there is stromal collagen disorganization and Bowman layer disruption.<br><br>The absence of significant inflammatory infiltrates differentiates keratoconus from ulcerative inflammatory corneal disorders.<br><br>Mooren ulcer (A) and peripheral ulcerative keratitis (C) are inflammatory destructive corneal conditions associated with severe pain and immune-mediated damage.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which contact lens type often provides best visual rehabilitation in keratoconus?","o":["Soft spherical lenses","Rigid gas-permeable lenses","Bifocal soft lenses","Bandage contact lenses","Cosmetic tinted lenses"],"a":1,"e":"Rigid gas-permeable contact lenses provide a smooth refractive surface over the irregular ectatic cornea and significantly improve visual acuity in keratoconus.<br><br>They reduce optical distortion caused by irregular astigmatism better than standard soft contact lenses.<br><br>Bandage lenses (D) are primarily used for epithelial healing rather than refractive correction of ectatic corneal disease.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which ectatic disorder is associated with acute corneal hydrops?","o":["Arcus senilis","Keratoconus","Band keratopathy","Pterygium","Fuchs dystrophy"],"a":1,"e":"Acute corneal hydrops occurs in advanced keratoconus due to rupture of Descemet membrane with sudden influx of aqueous into the corneal stroma.<br><br>Patients present with sudden painful visual deterioration, marked stromal edema, and corneal whitening. This ectatic corneal disorder with its classic signs is a heavily emphasised examination favourite.<br><br>Band keratopathy (C) involves superficial calcium deposition and does not produce acute stromal edema. Arcus senilis (A) is an asymptomatic peripheral lipid degeneration.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal ectasia is characterized by posterior corneal protrusion while anterior curvature remains relatively normal?","o":["Keratoglobus","Keratoconus","Pellucid marginal degeneration","Posterior keratoconus","Terrien marginal degeneration"],"a":3,"e":"Posterior keratoconus is a rare ectatic anomaly characterized by localized posterior corneal indentation or protrusion while the anterior corneal surface may remain relatively normal.<br><br>It is usually congenital and nonprogressive, although associated stromal scarring may impair vision.<br><br>Keratoconus (B) primarily affects the anterior corneal curvature with progressive conical protrusion and stromal thinning.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which feature differentiates pellucid marginal degeneration from keratoconus?","o":["Presence of irregular astigmatism","Inferior peripheral thinning","Progressive visual deterioration","Bilateral involvement","Noninflammatory nature"],"a":1,"e":"Pellucid marginal degeneration is distinguished by a narrow band of inferior peripheral corneal thinning, whereas keratoconus usually causes central or paracentral thinning.<br><br>The maximal protrusion in pellucid degeneration occurs above the area of thinning, producing characteristic topographic patterns.<br><br>Both conditions are bilateral, noninflammatory ectatic disorders associated with irregular astigmatism and progressive visual distortion.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal ectasia most commonly presents during puberty?","o":["Keratoconus","Arcus senilis","Band keratopathy","Terrien marginal degeneration","Posterior crocodile shagreen"],"a":0,"e":"Keratoconus typically begins around puberty and progresses during adolescence and early adulthood before stabilizing later in life.<br><br>Progressive irregular astigmatism and myopia cause frequent spectacle prescription changes and visual distortion in young patients.<br><br>Arcus senilis (B) and posterior crocodile shagreen (E) are age-related degenerative conditions rather than adolescent ectatic disorders.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which sign is produced by rupture of Bowman layer in keratoconus?","o":["Vogt striae","Munson sign","Apical scarring","Guttata","Band opacity"],"a":2,"e":"Rupture of Bowman layer in progressive keratoconus may lead to superficial apical scarring at the cone apex, contributing to visual impairment.<br><br>Chronic stromal stress and epithelial irregularity further promote scar formation in advanced disease.<br><br>Vogt striae (A) are stress lines in deep stroma and Descemet membrane rather than scars due to Bowman layer rupture.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which procedure is most appropriate for advanced keratoconus with central scarring and contact lens intolerance?","o":["Radial keratotomy","Corneal tattooing","Penetrating keratoplasty","Cyclodestructive surgery","Trabeculectomy"],"a":2,"e":"Penetrating keratoplasty is indicated in advanced keratoconus with severe central scarring, extreme thinning, or inability to tolerate contact lenses.<br><br>Corneal transplantation generally provides excellent visual prognosis because keratoconus rarely recurs aggressively in graft tissue. This ectatic corneal disorder with its classic signs is a heavily emphasised examination favourite.<br><br>Radial keratotomy (A) weakens the cornea further and may worsen ectasia. Trabeculectomy (E) is a glaucoma filtration procedure unrelated to ectatic corneal disease.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 22-year-old presents with progressive myopia and irregular astigmatism. Retinoscopy shows a scissor reflex. On downgaze, the pointed cornea produces a V-shaped indentation of the lower lid. What is this sign called?","o":["Munson sign","Rizutti sign","Vogt striae","Fleischer ring","Hydrops sign"],"a":0,"e":"Munson sign is a V-shaped indentation of the lower eyelid produced by the ectatic cone pushing against the lid on downgaze; it indicates advanced keratoconus and is visible to the naked eye without slit-lamp examination.<br><br>It results from the cone apex mechanically deforming the lower lid margin; its presence alongside scissor reflex and irregular astigmatism confirms advanced ectatic disease requiring urgent management planning. This ectatic corneal disorder with its classic signs is a heavily emphasised examination favourite.<br><br>Rizutti sign (B) is a conical nasal reflection when light shines from the temporal side; Vogt striae (C) are deep stromal stress lines; Fleischer ring (D) is iron deposition at the cone base; hydrops (E) is acute Descemet rupture.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 25-year-old with keratoconus has light shone from the temporal limbus. A bright conical reflection appears on the nasal cornea near the limbus. Which sign is this?","o":["Munson sign","Rizutti sign","Fleischer ring","Vogt striae","Oil"],"a":1,"e":"Rizutti sign is a conical bright reflection focused on the nasal limbus when light is directed from the temporal side; it occurs because the ectatic cone acts as a converging lens concentrating the light beam onto the nasal cornea.<br><br>It is a reliable sign of moderate to advanced keratoconus detectable with a simple pen torch; combined with Munson sign and Vogt striae it forms the classic clinical triad of advanced keratoconus on slit-lamp examination.<br><br>Munson sign (A) is lower lid V-shaped indentation on downgaze; Fleischer ring (C) is basal iron deposition; Vogt striae (D) are deep posterior stromal stress lines; oil droplet reflex (E) is a retinoscopic finding not a slit-lamp sign.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 20-year-old keratoconus patient develops sudden severe pain and acute vision loss. Slit-lamp shows central corneal oedema with a grey-white stromal opacity. IOP is normal. What has occurred?","o":["Bacterial keratitis","Acute angle closure glaucoma","Acute corneal hydrops","Corneal perforation","Descemet membrane detachment"],"a":2,"e":"Acute corneal hydrops results from a break in Descemet membrane allowing aqueous to flood the stroma; it presents with sudden pain, photophobia, and acute vision loss with central stromal and epithelial oedema visible on slit-lamp as a grey-white opacity.<br><br>Management is conservative with topical hypertonic saline, cycloplegics, and IOP-lowering agents; the oedema resolves over three to four months leaving a scar; intracameral gas injection accelerates resolution in refractory cases. This ectatic corneal disorder with its classic signs is a heavily emphasised examination favourite.<br><br>Bacterial keratitis (A) has mucopurulent discharge and ulceration; acute angle closure (B) has raised IOP and a shallow anterior chamber; corneal perforation (D) causes hypotony and iris prolapse; Descemet detachment (E) occurs postoperatively not spontaneously in keratoconus.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Vogt striae in keratoconus are located in which layer of the cornea?","o":["Epithelium","Bowman layer","Anterior stroma","Deep posterior stroma","Descemet membrane"],"a":3,"e":"Vogt striae are fine vertical stress lines located in the deep posterior stroma of keratoconus; they result from tension created by the thinning and ectatic cone stretching the posterior stromal lamellae and Descemet membrane producing these characteristic stress lines.<br><br>A pathognomonic feature is their temporary disappearance when gentle digital pressure is applied to the globe, momentarily relieving the tension; their presence on slit-lamp confirms moderate keratoconus and they are best seen with a narrow optic section beam. This ectatic corneal disorder with its classic signs is a heavily emphasised examination favourite.<br><br>Epithelium (A) is the site of Fleischer ring iron deposition; Bowman layer (B) develops breaks causing apical scarring in advanced disease; anterior stroma (C) is not the location of Vogt striae; Descemet membrane (E) ruptures to cause acute hydrops.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 18-year-old with Down syndrome presents with progressive bilateral visual deterioration. Corneal topography shows inferior steepening bilaterally. Which ectatic condition is most associated with Down syndrome?","o":["Pellucid marginal degeneration","Keratoglobus","Post-LASIK ectasia","Terrien marginal degeneration","Keratoconus"],"a":4,"e":"Keratoconus is strongly associated with Down syndrome occurring in approximately 15% of affected patients; the proposed mechanisms include chronic eye rubbing from atopic disease, connective tissue abnormalities, and oxidative stress causing corneal stromal weakening and progressive ectasia.<br><br>Other systemic associations include atopic dermatitis, Marfan syndrome, Ehlers-Danlos syndrome, Leber congenital amaurosis, and mitral valve prolapse; identifying keratoconus early in Down syndrome patients allows timely crosslinking to halt progression. This ectatic corneal disorder with its classic signs is a heavily emphasised examination favourite.<br><br>Pellucid marginal degeneration (A) is inferior peripheral thinning not specifically associated with Down syndrome; keratoglobus (B) is associated with Leber congenital amaurosis; post-LASIK ectasia (C) is iatrogenic; Terrien degeneration (D) is a peripheral non-ectatic condition.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 28-year-old with progressive keratoconus is no longer tolerating rigid gas permeable lenses. Corneal topography shows Kmax of 62 dioptres with central thinning to 380 microns. Which surgical option is most appropriate at this stage?","o":["Deep anterior lamellar keratoplasty","Corneal collagen crosslinking","LASIK refractive surgery","Phakic IOL implantation","Intacs segment"],"a":0,"e":"Deep anterior lamellar keratoplasty replaces the diseased anterior stroma while preserving the healthy host endothelium; it is preferred over penetrating keratoplasty in advanced keratoconus as it eliminates endothelial rejection risk while providing equivalent visual outcomes in eyes without stromal scarring.<br><br>DALK is preferred when central thinning is severe and contact lens wear is no longer tolerable; the big bubble technique achieves a clean plane of dissection at Descemet membrane; penetrating keratoplasty is reserved for cases with significant apical scarring. This ectatic corneal disorder with its classic signs is a heavily emphasised examination favourite.<br><br>Crosslinking (B) halts progression but cannot improve vision in advanced disease with 380 micron thinning; LASIK (C) is absolutely contraindicated in keratoconus; phakic IOL (D) does not address the ectasia; Intacs (E) are suitable for moderate not severe keratoconus.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 24-year-old presents with inferior peripheral corneal thinning 1 to 2 mm from the limbus. Topography shows a crab-claw or butterfly pattern with superior steepening. Fleischer ring is absent. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Keratoconus","Pellucid marginal degeneration","Keratoglobus","Terrien marginal degeneration","Post-LASIK ectasia"],"a":1,"e":"Pellucid marginal degeneration causes inferior peripheral clear corneal thinning 1 to 2 mm from the limbus with the classic crab-claw or butterfly topographic pattern from superior steepening; the absence of Fleischer ring and Vogt striae distinguishes it from keratoconus.<br><br>The condition causes against-the-rule astigmatism and progressive visual deterioration; RGP contact lenses are first-line optical management; large diameter eccentric DALK or penetrating keratoplasty is required for advanced cases intolerant of contact lenses. This ectatic corneal disorder with its classic signs is a heavily emphasised examination favourite.<br><br>Keratoconus (A) causes central or paracentral thinning with Fleischer ring; keratoglobus (C) causes global corneal thinning uniformly; Terrien degeneration (D) is superior peripheral with vascularisation; post-LASIK ectasia (E) follows refractive surgery with central thinning.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 30-year-old presents with global corneal thinning affecting the entire cornea uniformly producing a spherical globular appearance. The corneal thickness is 20% of normal throughout. Which systemic condition is most associated?","o":["Down syndrome","Marfan syndrome","Leber congenital amaurosis","Ehlers-Danlos syndrome","Osteogenesis imperfecta"],"a":2,"e":"Keratoglobus causing global uniform corneal thinning is most specifically associated with Leber congenital amaurosis among the listed options; the extreme thinning to 20% of normal thickness makes the cornea vulnerable to perforation from minor blunt trauma.<br><br>Additional associations include Ehlers-Danlos syndrome and congenital rubella; the management requires protective eyewear to prevent traumatic perforation; large diameter penetrating keratoplasty is technically challenging due to the peripheral thinning extending to the limbus. This ectatic corneal disorder with its classic signs is a heavily emphasised examination favourite.<br><br>Down syndrome (A) is associated with keratoconus not keratoglobus; Marfan syndrome (B) causes ectopia lentis; Ehlers-Danlos syndrome (D) is associated but Leber congenital amaurosis is the most specific association; osteogenesis imperfecta (E) causes blue sclerae not keratoglobus.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which investigation is the gold standard for detecting subclinical keratoconus before refractive surgery in a patient with normal slit-lamp examination?","o":["Specular microscopy","Corneal pachymetry alone","Placido disc topography","Scheimpflug-based corneal tomography","Anterior segment"],"a":3,"e":"Scheimpflug-based corneal tomography such as Pentacam analyses both anterior and posterior corneal surfaces, pachymetric maps, and elevation data simultaneously; posterior corneal elevation change is the earliest detectable sign of subclinical keratoconus before any anterior surface abnormality appears.<br><br>This multiparametric analysis makes it superior to Placido-based topography which analyses only the anterior surface; the Belin-Ambrosio enhanced ectasia display combines multiple parameters providing the highest sensitivity for detecting early ectasia before refractive surgery.<br><br>Specular microscopy (A) assesses endothelial cells; pachymetry alone (B) is insufficient as a single parameter; Placido disc topography (C) analyses only the anterior surface missing early posterior elevation changes; anterior segment OCT (D) provides structural data but not the comprehensive ectasia analysis of Scheimpflug tomography.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 26-year-old has progressive keratoconus with Kmax increasing by 2 dioptres over twelve months. Corneal thickness is 430 microns. Which treatment most specifically halts this progression?","o":["RGP contact lens fitting","Intacs corneal ring segments","Phakic IOL implantation","Topical vitamin C drops","Corneal collagen"],"a":4,"e":"Corneal collagen crosslinking using riboflavin and ultraviolet-A light creates new covalent bonds between collagen fibres within the stroma, increasing corneal biomechanical stiffness and halting ectatic progression; it is the only treatment proven to stop keratoconus progression.<br><br>The Dresden protocol requires minimum corneal thickness of 400 microns; accelerated crosslinking protocols achieve equivalent results in less time; early intervention before significant thinning preserves contact lens tolerance and delays or avoids keratoplasty. This ectatic corneal disorder with its classic signs is a heavily emphasised examination favourite.<br><br>RGP contact lenses (A) improve vision but do not halt progression; Intacs (B) reshape the cornea but do not stop progression; phakic IOL (C) corrects refractive error only; topical vitamin C (D) has no proven role in halting keratoconus progression.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 35-year-old develops progressive myopia, irregular astigmatism, and decreased vision two years after LASIK surgery. Topography shows inferior steepening with central thinning. Residual stromal bed thickness was 80 microns postoperatively. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Post-LASIK ectasia","Decentred ablation","Primary keratoconus","Pellucid marginal degeneration","Flap dislocation"],"a":0,"e":"Post-LASIK ectasia occurs when insufficient residual stromal bed thickness following ablation leaves the cornea biomechanically compromised; the minimum safe residual stromal bed is 250 to 300 microns; 80 microns is critically insufficient making iatrogenic ectasia inevitable in a susceptible cornea.<br><br>Risk factors include preoperative subclinical keratoconus, high myopic correction, thin preoperative cornea, and inadequate residual bed; management involves crosslinking to halt progression and RGP lenses or keratoplasty for visual rehabilitation. This ectatic corneal disorder with its classic signs is a heavily emphasised examination favourite.<br><br>Decentred ablation (B) causes coma aberrations without progressive thinning; primary keratoconus (C) predates surgery; pellucid marginal degeneration (D) has inferior peripheral not central thinning; flap dislocation (E) causes acute hazing not progressive ectasia.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which refractive surgical procedure carries the lowest risk of postoperative corneal ectasia compared to LASIK in a patient with borderline topography?","o":["LASIK with thin flap","LASEK with alcohol epithelial flap","SMILE small incision lenticule extraction","PRK photorefractive keratectomy","Femtosecond LASIK"],"a":3,"e":"PRK carries a lower ectasia risk than LASIK because no stromal flap is created; the entire treatment depth contributes to the residual stromal bed and there is no flap-related biomechanical weakening; this makes PRK the preferred refractive procedure in patients with borderline topography or thin corneas.<br><br>SMILE also carries lower ectasia risk than LASIK; however, PRK remains the most established and safest surface ablation option for borderline cases due to decades of safety data compared to the more recent SMILE procedure.<br><br>LASIK with thin flap (A) still creates a flap weakening the anterior stroma; SMILE (C) is safer than LASIK but PRK has more long-term safety evidence; LASEK (B) still weakens Bowman layer; femtosecond LASIK (E) creates a more uniform flap but still carries ectasia risk.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 22-year-old with moderate keratoconus tolerates RGP lenses poorly. Corneal topography shows Kmax of 54 dioptres with 450 micron thickness. He wishes to avoid keratoplasty. Which surgical option is most appropriate?","o":["Deep anterior lamellar keratoplasty","Penetrating keratoplasty","Intacs corneal ring segment implantation","Crosslinking alone","Phakic"],"a":2,"e":"Intacs are PMMA ring segments implanted within the mid-peripheral corneal stroma at approximately two-thirds depth; they flatten the central cone redistributing corneal curvature, improving topography, and enhancing contact lens tolerance, acting as a bridge delaying or avoiding keratoplasty.<br><br>They are most effective in moderate keratoconus with Kmax below 55 dioptres and adequate central corneal thickness; crosslinking can be combined with Intacs for simultaneous progression halting and topographic improvement in suitable candidates. This ectatic corneal disorder with its classic signs is a heavily emphasised examination favourite.<br><br>DALK (A) and penetrating keratoplasty (B) are definitive but this patient specifically wishes to avoid keratoplasty; crosslinking alone (D) halts progression but does not improve vision or contact lens tolerance; phakic IOL (E) corrects refractive error but does not address the ectasia.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"The oil droplet reflex seen on retinoscopy in keratoconus results from which optical phenomenon?","o":["Total internal reflection at the cone apex","Irregular astigmatism causing scissor reflex artefact","Light scattering from stromal scarring","The cone acting as a converging lens creating a central bright reflex","Corneal oedema producing a diffuse glow"],"a":3,"e":"The oil droplet reflex is seen on direct ophthalmoscopy or retinoscopy when the ectatic cone acts as a small converging lens; this concentrates the reflected light into a central bright spot surrounded by a dark ring, resembling an oil droplet, and is pathognomonic of keratoconus.<br><br>It is best appreciated using the direct ophthalmoscope held at arm's length; the sign is present before the classic slit-lamp signs become visible making it a valuable early diagnostic indicator in patients with unexplained poor spectacle-corrected visual acuity.<br><br>Total internal reflection (A) is not the mechanism; scissor reflex (B) is a retinoscopy finding from irregular astigmatism distinct from the oil droplet sign; stromal scarring scatter (C) produces haze not a focal bright spot; corneal oedema (E) produces a diffuse not focal reflex.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 19-year-old atopic patient with chronic eye rubbing presents with progressive keratoconus. Which single most modifiable risk factor should be immediately addressed?","o":["Contact lens wear cessation","Topical steroid use","Dietary vitamin supplementation","Sunlight exposure avoidance","Eye rubbing cessation"],"a":4,"e":"Chronic vigorous eye rubbing is the most important modifiable risk factor in keratoconus progression; repeated mechanical trauma releases corneal epithelial inflammatory cytokines including IL-1 and TNF-alpha activating matrix metalloproteinases that degrade stromal collagen causing progressive thinning and ectasia.<br><br>Patients with atopic disease are particularly susceptible; addressing the underlying atopy with antihistamines and mast cell stabilisers reduces the itch-rub cycle; stopping eye rubbing alongside crosslinking provides the most effective combined approach to halting keratoconus progression. This ectatic corneal disorder with its classic signs is a heavily emphasised examination favourite.<br><br>Contact lens wear cessation (A) is important before surgery but does not halt ectasia; topical steroids (B) manage atopy but do not directly address the mechanical rubbing; dietary supplements (C) have no proven role; sunlight avoidance (D) has minimal evidence for keratoconus prevention.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 17-year-old presents with scissor reflex on retinoscopy, inferior corneal steepening on topography, and posterior elevation of plus 18 microns on Scheimpflug tomography. Slit-lamp examination is entirely normal. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Subclinical keratoconus","Normal topographic variant","Pellucid marginal degeneration","Early Fuchs dystrophy","Post-infectious"],"a":0,"e":"Subclinical keratoconus presents with abnormal tomographic indices including posterior elevation exceeding 16 microns, inferior steepening on topography, and abnormal pachymetric progression maps despite a completely normal slit-lamp examination with no clinical signs.<br><br>Early diagnosis is critical to prevent offering refractive surgery which would risk iatrogenic ectasia; these patients require preventive crosslinking if progression is documented and should avoid LASIK permanently regardless of apparent stability on follow-up. This ectatic corneal disorder with its classic signs is a heavily emphasised examination favourite.<br><br>Normal topographic variant (B) does not show posterior elevation abnormality combined with inferior steepening; pellucid marginal degeneration (C) has peripheral not central posterior elevation; early Fuchs dystrophy (D) shows endothelial guttae; post-infectious scarring (E) has a history of keratitis.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which collagen crosslinking protocol is the standard Dresden protocol and what are its key parameters?","o":["UV-A 9 mW/cm2 for 10 minutes with riboflavin","UV-A 3 mW/cm2 for 30 minutes with riboflavin","UV-A 45 mW/cm2 for 2 minutes with riboflavin","UV-A 30 mW/cm2 for 8 minutes with riboflavin","UV-A 10 mW/cm2 for 9"],"a":1,"e":"The Dresden protocol uses UV-A irradiance of 3 mW/cm2 for 30 minutes delivering a total energy fluence of 5.4 J/cm2; riboflavin 0.1% is instilled every 2 minutes for 30 minutes prior to UV-A exposure to act as a photosensitiser generating reactive oxygen species crosslinking collagen.<br><br>Epithelium is debrided to allow riboflavin penetration to the stroma; minimum corneal thickness of 400 microns must be confirmed before treatment to protect the endothelium from UV-A damage beyond the stroma.<br><br>9 mW/cm2 for 10 minutes (A) is an accelerated protocol not Dresden; 45 mW/cm2 for 2 minutes (C) is a high-intensity accelerated protocol; 30 mW/cm2 for 8 minutes (D) is another accelerated variant; 10 mW/cm2 for 9 minutes (E) does not represent any standard protocol.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 32-year-old post-keratoplasty patient for keratoconus develops recurrent irregular astigmatism and inferior steepening in the graft five years after penetrating keratoplasty. What has occurred?","o":["Graft rejection episode","Suture-related astigmatism","Recurrence of keratoconus in the donor graft","Primary graft failure","Posterior"],"a":2,"e":"Keratoconus can recur in the donor corneal button following penetrating keratoplasty; the host keratoconic environment transfers ectatic signals possibly through mechanical stress, cytokine milieu, or epigenetic factors to the donor stroma causing progressive ectatic changes in the graft tissue.<br><br>Recurrence is more common after deep anterior lamellar keratoplasty than penetrating keratoplasty; regular topographic monitoring post-keratoplasty detects early recurrence; crosslinking of the donor graft has been used successfully to halt recurrent ectasia. This ectatic corneal disorder with its classic signs is a heavily emphasised examination favourite.<br><br>Graft rejection (A) presents with subepithelial infiltrates, keratic precipitates, and endothelial rejection line; suture astigmatism (B) is caused by uneven suture tension not progressive ectasia; primary graft failure (D) presents early postoperatively; posterior polymorphous dystrophy (E) is a primary endothelial condition.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which slit-lamp finding in keratoconus temporarily disappears when gentle digital pressure is applied to the closed eyelid?","o":["Fleischer ring","Apical scarring","Rizutti sign","Vogt striae","Munson sign"],"a":3,"e":"Vogt striae are deep posterior stromal stress lines produced by tension from the ectatic cone; applying gentle digital pressure to the globe temporarily relieves this tension causing the striae to disappear momentarily; this pressure-related disappearance is pathognomonic and differentiates them from other corneal lines.<br><br>This bedside test can be performed at the slit-lamp; the striae reappear immediately when pressure is released; their presence indicates moderate keratoconus and they are best visualised using a narrow optic section beam directed at the deep posterior stroma.<br><br>Fleischer ring (A) is an iron deposition ring unaffected by pressure; apical scarring (B) is a fixed stromal scar; Rizutti sign (C) is an optical reflection from the cone; Munson sign (E) is a lower lid deformity not a corneal slit-lamp finding.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 21-year-old presents with keratoconus and a spectacle-corrected acuity of 6/36 from irregular astigmatism. RGP lenses improve vision to 6/6. Crosslinking was performed six months ago confirming stable disease. What is the most appropriate next management step?","o":["Immediate penetrating keratoplasty","Intacs ring segment implantation","Repeat crosslinking procedure","Phakic IOL implantation","Continue RGP lens wear with regular monitoring"],"a":4,"e":"Stable keratoconus after confirmed crosslinking achieving 6/6 with RGP lenses requires no further surgical intervention; RGP lenses are the gold standard for visual rehabilitation in keratoconus providing excellent acuity by masking the irregular corneal surface with a regular refractive interface.<br><br>Surgery is reserved for contact lens intolerance, inadequate lens-corrected vision, or documented progression despite crosslinking; regular six-monthly topographic monitoring ensures stability is maintained and any future progression is detected early.<br><br>Penetrating keratoplasty (A) is premature when RGP lenses achieve 6/6; Intacs (B) are indicated for contact lens intolerance not successful lens wear; repeat crosslinking (C) is not indicated for confirmed stable disease; phakic IOL (D) does not address irregular astigmatism.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which refractive surgical procedure reshapes the corneal stroma using an excimer laser beneath a corneal flap?","o":["PRK","Radial keratotomy","Corneal collagen cross-linking","Penetrating keratoplasty","LASIK"],"a":4,"e":"LASIK involves creation of a corneal flap followed by excimer laser ablation of stromal tissue to correct refractive error. The flap is then repositioned without sutures.<br><br>The procedure provides rapid visual recovery and minimal postoperative discomfort compared with surface ablation techniques such as PRK.<br><br>PRK (A) removes the corneal epithelium without creating a stromal flap. Corneal collagen cross-linking (C) stabilizes ectasia rather than primarily correcting refractive error.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which refractive surgery complication is characterized by progressive corneal thinning and protrusion after LASIK?","o":["Bullous keratopathy","Hypopyon","Corneal guttata","Band keratopathy","Post-LASIK ectasia"],"a":4,"e":"Post-LASIK ectasia is a progressive biomechanical weakening disorder causing corneal thinning, protrusion, and irregular astigmatism after refractive surgery.<br><br>Risk factors include preexisting forme fruste keratoconus, thin corneas, and excessive stromal ablation depth.<br><br>Bullous keratopathy (A) results from endothelial failure rather than stromal biomechanical instability. Band keratopathy (D) is a superficial calcium deposition disorder.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which laser is primarily used in excimer laser refractive surgery?","o":["Nd:YAG laser","Argon laser","Excimer laser","Diode laser","Krypton laser"],"a":2,"e":"Excimer laser emits ultraviolet light that precisely photoablates corneal stromal tissue with minimal thermal damage to adjacent structures.<br><br>It is the principal laser used in PRK and LASIK procedures for correction of myopia, hyperopia, and astigmatism.<br><br>Nd:YAG laser (A) is commonly used for posterior capsulotomy rather than corneal refractive ablation. Argon laser (B) is mainly retinal photocoagulation laser.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which refractive procedure removes the corneal epithelium before excimer laser ablation without creating a flap?","o":["LASIK","PRK","SMILE","Keratoplasty","Intracorneal ring implantation"],"a":1,"e":"Photorefractive keratectomy involves removal of corneal epithelium followed by excimer laser ablation of anterior stromal tissue to reshape the cornea.<br><br>Visual recovery is slower and postoperative discomfort is greater than LASIK because epithelial healing must occur.<br><br>LASIK (A) creates a corneal flap before stromal ablation. SMILE (C) removes a stromal lenticule through a small incision instead of epithelial removal.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal refractive surgery complication commonly presents with glare and halos at night?","o":["Endophthalmitis","Retinal detachment","Orbital cellulitis","Hypopyon","Higher-order aberrations"],"a":4,"e":"Higher-order optical aberrations after refractive surgery may cause glare, halos, reduced contrast sensitivity, and poor night vision despite good visual acuity.<br><br>These symptoms are more common with decentered ablation or large pupil size under dim illumination.<br><br>Endophthalmitis (A) presents with painful severe inflammation rather than isolated nighttime visual disturbances. Retinal detachment (B) causes flashes and floaters.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which procedure is specifically designed to halt progression of keratoconus?","o":["Radial keratotomy","LASIK","Corneal collagen cross-linking","Automated lamellar keratoplasty","Conductive keratoplasty"],"a":2,"e":"Corneal collagen cross-linking uses riboflavin and ultraviolet-A irradiation to strengthen stromal collagen bonds and stabilize progressive ectasia.<br><br>It is particularly effective in halting progression of keratoconus and post-LASIK ectasia in younger patients.<br><br>LASIK (B) reshapes the cornea but may worsen ectasia in predisposed individuals. Radial keratotomy (A) weakens corneal biomechanics further.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which refractive surgery is most strongly associated with corneal haze during healing?","o":["LASIK","PRK","SMILE","Intrastromal ring implantation","Phakic IOL implantation"],"a":1,"e":"PRK may produce postoperative subepithelial corneal haze because stromal wound healing occurs directly beneath the regenerating epithelium.<br><br>Mitomycin-C is sometimes used intraoperatively to reduce haze formation in high refractive corrections.<br><br>LASIK (A) generally causes less haze because the stromal surface remains covered by the corneal flap. SMILE (C) avoids large epithelial defects.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which refractive procedure corrects myopia by implanting a lens without removing the natural crystalline lens?","o":["Clear lens extraction","Penetrating keratoplasty","PRK only","LASIK only","Phakic intraocular lens implantation"],"a":4,"e":"Phakic intraocular lenses correct high refractive errors while preserving the patient's natural crystalline lens and accommodation.<br><br>They are especially useful in high myopia unsuitable for corneal refractive surgery because of thin corneas or excessive refractive error.<br><br>Clear lens extraction (A) removes the natural lens and sacrifices accommodation. LASIK (D) reshapes the cornea instead of implanting an intraocular lens.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which refractive surgery complication results from incomplete corneal flap creation?","o":["Buttonhole flap","Hypopyon","Cataract","Choroidal detachment","Vitreous hemorrhage"],"a":0,"e":"Buttonhole flap is a LASIK flap complication caused by incomplete or irregular flap formation during microkeratome or femtosecond laser dissection.<br><br>It may lead to irregular astigmatism, epithelial ingrowth, and poor visual quality if surgery proceeds despite flap damage.<br><br>Hypopyon (B) indicates anterior chamber inflammation rather than flap-related stromal complications. Cataract (C) is unrelated to corneal flap formation.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which refractive surgical technique removes a stromal lenticule through a small incision?","o":["PRK","LASIK","SMILE","Radial keratotomy","Automated lamellar keratoplasty"],"a":2,"e":"SMILE, or small-incision lenticule extraction, uses a femtosecond laser to create and remove a stromal lenticule through a small corneal incision.<br><br>The procedure preserves more anterior corneal biomechanics and causes less dry eye compared with LASIK because no large flap is created.<br><br>PRK (A) removes epithelium for surface ablation rather than extracting stromal lenticules. Radial keratotomy (D) uses corneal incisions instead of laser lenticule removal.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal transplant replaces only diseased endothelium while preserving anterior stroma?","o":["Penetrating keratoplasty","Deep anterior lamellar keratoplasty","SMILE","Radial keratotomy","Endothelial keratoplasty"],"a":4,"e":"Endothelial keratoplasty selectively replaces diseased Descemet membrane and endothelium while preserving healthy anterior stromal tissue.<br><br>It is commonly performed for endothelial disorders such as Fuchs dystrophy and pseudophakic bullous keratopathy.<br><br>Deep anterior lamellar keratoplasty (B) preserves endothelium but replaces anterior stromal layers instead. Penetrating keratoplasty (A) replaces full-thickness cornea.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which complication is more common after LASIK than PRK?","o":["Corneal haze","Stromal scarring","Painful epithelial healing","Delayed epithelial recovery","Flap displacement"],"a":4,"e":"LASIK uniquely involves creation of a corneal flap, making flap displacement or dislocation a potential postoperative complication, particularly after trauma.<br><br>Patients are advised to avoid vigorous eye rubbing during early healing because flap adherence initially remains weak.<br><br>PRK (A) does not create a flap and therefore cannot produce flap displacement. Corneal haze is more characteristic of PRK healing responses.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which refractive surgery is contraindicated in progressive keratoconus?","o":["Corneal collagen cross-linking","Penetrating keratoplasty","LASIK","Intracorneal ring segments","Rigid gas-permeable lenses"],"a":2,"e":"LASIK is contraindicated in progressive keratoconus because stromal tissue removal further weakens corneal biomechanics and may accelerate ectasia.<br><br>Preoperative corneal topography screening is essential to detect subclinical keratoconus before refractive surgery.<br><br>Collagen cross-linking (A) is used therapeutically to stabilize ectatic progression rather than worsen it. Intracorneal ring segments (D) may improve corneal shape in selected cases.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal transplantation procedure preserves host endothelium?","o":["Penetrating keratoplasty","Endothelial keratoplasty","Descemet stripping endothelial keratoplasty","Keratoprosthesis","Deep anterior lamellar keratoplasty"],"a":4,"e":"Deep anterior lamellar keratoplasty replaces diseased anterior corneal stroma while preserving healthy host Descemet membrane and endothelium.<br><br>This reduces the risk of endothelial rejection compared with full-thickness penetrating keratoplasty.<br><br>Endothelial keratoplasty (B) specifically replaces diseased endothelium instead of preserving it. Penetrating keratoplasty (A) replaces all corneal layers.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which postoperative symptom is most common after PRK during early healing?","o":["Severe painless visual loss","Marked postoperative pain","Hypopyon formation","Choroidal hemorrhage","Retinal detachment"],"a":1,"e":"PRK causes significant postoperative discomfort because the corneal epithelium is removed, exposing corneal nerve endings during epithelial regeneration.<br><br>Pain, photophobia, tearing, and foreign-body sensation are common during the first few postoperative days.<br><br>LASIK generally causes much less discomfort because the epithelial surface remains largely intact beneath the repositioned flap. Hypopyon (C) is not expected in uncomplicated PRK recovery.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which refractive surgery technique weakens corneal biomechanics by making radial corneal incisions?","o":["LASIK","PRK","Radial keratotomy","SMILE","Collagen cross-linking"],"a":2,"e":"Radial keratotomy corrects myopia by making deep radial corneal incisions that flatten the central cornea. The technique is now largely obsolete.<br><br>Long-term complications include unstable refraction, progressive hyperopic shift, and biomechanical weakening of the cornea.<br><br>Collagen cross-linking (E) strengthens corneal biomechanics rather than weakening them. LASIK (A) uses laser stromal ablation instead of radial incisions.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal surgery complication may present with epithelial cells growing beneath the LASIK flap?","o":["Corneal guttata","Epithelial ingrowth","Descemetocele","Band keratopathy","Corneal hydrops"],"a":1,"e":"Epithelial ingrowth occurs when surface epithelial cells migrate beneath the LASIK flap interface, potentially causing visual distortion and flap melting.<br><br>Small peripheral ingrowth may remain asymptomatic, whereas progressive central ingrowth may require flap lifting and debridement.<br><br>Corneal hydrops (E) occurs in keratoconus due to Descemet membrane rupture rather than postoperative epithelial migration. Descemetocele (C) results from severe stromal ulceration.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which procedure is preferred for endothelial failure due to Fuchs dystrophy?","o":["Radial keratotomy","PRK","Intracorneal ring implantation","LASIK","Endothelial keratoplasty"],"a":4,"e":"Endothelial keratoplasty selectively replaces diseased endothelial tissue while preserving healthy anterior corneal layers in disorders such as Fuchs dystrophy.<br><br>Compared with penetrating keratoplasty, visual recovery is faster and postoperative astigmatism is less significant.<br><br>LASIK (D) is a refractive procedure and does not treat endothelial dysfunction. Intracorneal ring implantation (C) is used mainly in ectatic disorders such as keratoconus.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which factor is most important before performing corneal refractive surgery?","o":["Gonioscopy only","Schirmer test only","Fundus photography only","Amsler grid testing","Corneal topography screening"],"a":4,"e":"Corneal topography is essential before refractive surgery to detect keratoconus, forme fruste ectasia, and irregular corneal curvature patterns.<br><br>Failure to identify preexisting ectatic disorders significantly increases the risk of postoperative corneal ectasia.<br><br>Amsler grid testing (D) evaluates macular function rather than corneal biomechanics. Gonioscopy (A) is mainly used in glaucoma assessment.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which refractive surgery complication commonly causes fluctuating vision and ocular dryness?","o":["Dry eye syndrome","Hypopyon","Corneal perforation","Endophthalmitis","Retinal vein occlusion"],"a":0,"e":"Dry eye syndrome is a common complication after corneal refractive surgery because corneal nerve transection reduces reflex tear secretion and blink feedback.<br><br>Patients may experience fluctuating vision, burning, foreign-body sensation, and ocular discomfort, particularly after LASIK.<br><br>Hypopyon (B) and endophthalmitis (D) are severe inflammatory or infectious conditions not typically associated with uncomplicated refractive surgery recovery.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 28-year-old myope undergoes LASIK. During microkeratome pass the flap is made but is extremely thin and buttonholed centrally. What is the most appropriate immediate management?","o":["Replace the flap and abort surgery","Complete the ablation through the buttonhole","Lift the flap and proceed with ablation","Convert immediately to PRK","Apply bandage contact lens only"],"a":0,"e":"A buttonhole flap is a central perforation of the LASIK flap caused by an excessively thin microkeratome pass; the flap must be immediately replaced and surgery aborted to allow complete healing before considering an alternative approach.<br><br>Attempting ablation through a buttonhole causes irregular ablation, central scarring, and permanent visual loss; PRK can be safely offered three to six months later once the flap has fully healed and the corneal surface has stabilised completely.<br><br>Completing ablation through the buttonhole (B) causes irreversible central scarring; lifting and proceeding (C) worsens the buttonhole; immediate PRK conversion (D) is contraindicated through a disrupted epithelium; bandage contact lens alone (E) without replacing the flap is insufficient management.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 30-year-old undergoes LASIK and develops diffuse lamellar keratitis on day two postoperatively. The interface shows a diffuse white cell infiltrate grade two. What is the first-line treatment?","o":["Topical antifungal drops","Intensive topical corticosteroids","Immediate flap lift and irrigation","Systemic antibiotics","Nd:YAG"],"a":1,"e":"Diffuse lamellar keratitis is a sterile inflammatory reaction within the LASIK interface caused by meibomian secretions, endotoxins, or metallic debris; grade one and two disease responds excellently to intensive topical corticosteroids administered hourly with gradual tapering over two to four weeks.<br><br>Grade three and four disease with central interface involvement and vision loss requires flap lifting and irrigation combined with topical steroids; early recognition and aggressive steroid treatment prevents progression to corneal melt and permanent visual loss.<br><br>Topical antifungals (A) are inappropriate for a sterile inflammation; immediate flap lift (C) is reserved for grade three and four disease; systemic antibiotics (D) have no role in sterile DLK; Nd:YAG laser (E) is not used for interface inflammation.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 35-year-old myope with -8.00 dioptres myopia and 490 micron corneal thickness wishes refractive surgery. Posterior corneal elevation is normal. Which refractive procedure is most appropriate?","o":["LASIK with standard flap","Femtosecond LASIK","Phakic IOL implantation","PRK surface ablation","SMILE lenticule extraction"],"a":2,"e":"High myopia of -8.00 dioptres with a 490 micron cornea would leave an inadequate residual stromal bed after LASIK ablation; phakic IOL implantation adds refractive power without removing stromal tissue, preserving full corneal biomechanical integrity and avoiding ectasia risk entirely.<br><br>The Implantable Collamer Lens is the most commonly used phakic IOL; preoperative assessment requires adequate anterior chamber depth exceeding 3 mm and sufficient endothelial cell count to safely accommodate the lens without endothelial touch.<br><br>Standard LASIK (A) and femtosecond LASIK (B) would leave insufficient residual stromal bed; PRK (D) removes the same tissue volume as LASIK without a flap; SMILE (E) also removes stromal tissue insufficient for this level of correction with this corneal thickness.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 25-year-old undergoes PRK. On day three she has severe pain and photophobia. Slit-lamp shows diffuse punctate epithelial erosions and subepithelial haze developing. What is the most likely complication?","o":["Bacterial keratitis","Viral reactivation","Steroid-induced IOP rise","Delayed epithelial healing with haze formation","Corneal ectasia"],"a":3,"e":"Subepithelial haze following PRK results from aberrant keratocyte activation producing disorganised type three collagen in the anterior stroma; it is more common with high myopic corrections and delayed epithelial healing; mitomycin C 0.02% applied intraoperatively for 12 to 30 seconds significantly reduces haze formation.<br><br>Risk factors include high ablation depth, UV exposure, and inadequate postoperative topical steroid use; haze typically peaks at three months and may slowly resolve; severe haze requires phototherapeutic keratectomy for removal if vision is significantly affected.<br><br>Bacterial keratitis (A) causes focal ulceration not diffuse punctate erosions; viral reactivation (B) causes dendritic ulceration; steroid IOP rise (C) causes no epithelial changes; corneal ectasia (E) presents months later not on day three postoperatively.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 40-year-old undergoes penetrating keratoplasty for keratoconus. Six weeks postoperatively she develops a circumferential subepithelial infiltrate in the graft with a rejection line advancing from the limbus. What type of rejection is this?","o":["Primary graft failure","Endothelial rejection","Stromal rejection","Epithelial rejection","Subepithelial rejection"],"a":4,"e":"Subepithelial rejection in penetrating keratoplasty presents as fine subepithelial infiltrates resembling adenoviral keratoconjunctivitis; it follows the same pattern as epidemic keratoconjunctivitis but occurs in the donor tissue and represents an immune response against donor stromal antigens.<br><br>Vision is usually preserved as the endothelium remains unaffected; intensive topical corticosteroids reverse the infiltrates; subepithelial rejection rarely leads to graft failure unless it is a precursor to more serious endothelial rejection which must be monitored carefully.<br><br>Primary graft failure (A) presents immediately postoperatively with oedema; endothelial rejection (B) causes stromal oedema and Khodadoust line of keratic precipitates; stromal rejection (C) causes stromal infiltration and neovascularisation; epithelial rejection (D) causes a rejection line at the epithelial level not subepithelially.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"The Khodadoust line seen in corneal graft rejection represents which pathological process?","o":["Epithelial rejection line advancing across the graft","Stromal neovascularisation front advancing centrally","Subepithelial infiltrate line from viral infection","Endothelial rejection line of inflammatory cells advancing across the donor endothelium","Descemet membrane folds"],"a":3,"e":"The Khodadoust line is a line of keratic precipitates on the donor endothelium representing the advancing front of host T-lymphocytes attacking donor endothelial cells; it is the hallmark of endothelial rejection, the most visually devastating form of corneal graft rejection.<br><br>Emergency treatment with hourly topical prednisolone and systemic steroids can reverse endothelial rejection if initiated immediately; each rejection episode causes irreversible endothelial cell loss and may ultimately lead to graft failure requiring regrafting.<br><br>Epithelial rejection line (A) causes a line in the epithelium not on the endothelium; stromal neovascularisation (B) is a risk factor for rejection not the line itself; subepithelial infiltrates (C) represent subepithelial rejection; Descemet folds (E) are a consequence of oedema not the rejection line itself.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 45-year-old undergoes Descemet membrane endothelial keratoplasty for Fuchs dystrophy. On day one the graft is partially detached. What is the most appropriate management?","o":["Immediate regrafting with new donor tissue","Rebubbling with intracameral air injection","Topical steroids and observation for one week","Penetrating keratoplasty conversion immediately","Hypertonic"],"a":1,"e":"Partial DMEK graft detachment is managed by intracameral air injection to rebubble the graft against the host Descemet membrane; the patient is positioned face-up for one hour allowing the air bubble to press the donor graft into contact with the stripped host Descemet membrane promoting adherence.<br><br>Rebubbling is successful in the majority of cases; multiple rebubbling attempts may be required; persistent detachment after two to three failed attempts necessitates donor graft exchange; early rebubbling within the first two weeks gives the best outcomes.<br><br>Immediate regrafting (A) is premature before rebubbling attempts; topical steroids and observation (C) are insufficient for a detached graft; penetrating keratoplasty conversion (D) is a last resort; hypertonic saline (E) reduces oedema but cannot reattach a detached graft.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 32-year-old undergoes LASIK for -5.00 dioptres myopia. Postoperatively he experiences monocular diplopia and ghosting. Wavefront analysis shows increased coma. What is the most likely cause?","o":["Flap dislocation","Dry eye syndrome","Subepithelial haze formation","Diffuse lamellar keratitis","Decentred ablation zone"],"a":4,"e":"Decentred ablation creates an asymmetric corneal profile that generates higher-order aberrations particularly coma; the visual cortex receives multiple overlapping images from the decentred optical zone causing monocular diplopia, ghosting, and halos that are not correctable with spectacles.<br><br>Prevention requires accurate centration using pupil tracking and fixation light during ablation; treatment options include wavefront-guided enhancement to redistribute the ablation more symmetrically or rigid gas permeable lens fitting to mask the corneal irregularity optically.<br><br>Flap dislocation (A) causes immediate hazy vision with folds; dry eye (B) causes fluctuating blurred vision not fixed monocular diplopia; DLK (D) causes diffuse haze not coma; subepithelial haze (C) reduces contrast sensitivity not causing coma-type diplopia.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 38-year-old undergoes penetrating keratoplasty. At one year postoperatively her refraction shows 6.00 dioptres of astigmatism. What is the most appropriate initial management?","o":["Rigid gas permeable contact lens fitting","Topical steroid increase","Immediate selective suture removal","Repeat penetrating keratoplasty","Corneal relaxing incisions immediately"],"a":2,"e":"Post-keratoplasty astigmatism of 6.00 dioptres at one year is most effectively reduced by selective removal of tight sutures at the steep meridian; sutures on the steep axis are identified using keratometry or topography-guided assessment and selectively removed to allow wound relaxation and flattening.<br><br>Suture removal must be timed carefully; premature removal risks wound dehiscence while delayed removal allows permanent suture-induced topographic changes; after full suture removal at 18 months, residual astigmatism is addressed with RGP lenses or surgical correction.<br><br>RGP contact lens fitting (A) is appropriate after suture removal not instead of it; topical steroid increase (B) does not reduce astigmatism; repeat keratoplasty (D) is not indicated for astigmatism alone; corneal relaxing incisions (E) are performed after all sutures are removed.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 29-year-old myope undergoes SMILE small incision lenticule extraction. Which specific advantage does SMILE have over LASIK regarding corneal nerve preservation?","o":["SMILE uses less laser energy","SMILE creates a thinner effective optical zone","SMILE preserves more anterior stromal collagen lamellae","SMILE uses riboflavin as a photosensitiser","SMILE preserves"],"a":4,"e":"SMILE creates a lenticule within the stroma extracted through a small 2 to 4 mm incision without creating a flap; this preserves the anterior stromal nerve plexus which is extensively severed by the LASIK flap, resulting in significantly lower rates of postoperative dry eye and faster neurosensory recovery.<br><br>The preserved nerve architecture maintains corneal sensation, tear reflex integrity, and epithelial trophic support more effectively than LASIK; this makes SMILE the preferred procedure for patients at high risk of post-LASIK dry eye disease.<br><br>Less laser energy (A) does not specifically relate to nerve preservation; thinner optical zone (B) is a disadvantage not advantage of SMILE; anterior stromal collagen preservation (C) is a benefit but not the nerve-specific advantage; riboflavin (D) is used in crosslinking not SMILE.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 50-year-old woman with Fuchs endothelial dystrophy and a visually significant cataract requires surgery. Which surgical approach provides the best outcome?","o":["Combined phacoemulsification and DMEK in a single procedure","Phacoemulsification alone first then DMEK later","DMEK alone without addressing the cataract","Penetrating keratoplasty with simultaneous ECCE","Medical management with hypertonic saline indefinitely"],"a":0,"e":"Combined phacoemulsification and DMEK in a single surgical sitting is the preferred approach for patients with visually significant cataract and Fuchs dystrophy; it eliminates the need for two separate surgeries and anaesthetic exposures while treating both pathologies simultaneously with equivalent outcomes to staged procedures.<br><br>The cataract surgery is performed first followed immediately by Descemet stripping and DMEK graft insertion; IOL power calculation must account for the expected corneal curvature change after endothelial replacement using modified formulae specifically validated for post-DMEK refraction.<br><br>Phacoemulsification alone (B) risks accelerating endothelial decompensation from phaco energy in an already compromised endothelium; DMEK alone (C) does not address the cataract; penetrating keratoplasty with ECCE (D) is the older triple procedure now largely replaced; medical management (E) is not a long-term solution.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 22-year-old patient undergoes corneal collagen crosslinking for progressive keratoconus. The minimum corneal thickness required before UV-A application to ensure endothelial safety is?","o":["350 microns","400 microns","450 microns","500 microns","300"],"a":1,"e":"The minimum corneal thickness of 400 microns is required before UV-A exposure in the Dresden crosslinking protocol; below this threshold the UV-A radiation penetrates to the endothelium causing irreversible endothelial cell damage; pachymetry is measured after epithelial debridement and riboflavin instillation.<br><br>For corneas thinner than 400 microns, hypo-osmolar riboflavin is instilled to swell the cornea above the safety threshold; accelerated crosslinking protocols and transepithelial crosslinking are also options for thin corneas though their efficacy data continues to evolve.<br><br>350 microns (A) is below the safe threshold risking endothelial damage; 450 microns (C) and 500 microns (D) exceed the minimum providing additional safety margin; 300 microns (E) is critically unsafe and absolutely contraindicated for standard crosslinking.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 36-year-old develops epithelial ingrowth under a LASIK flap two months postoperatively. Vision has decreased to 6/18. The ingrowth has reached within 2 mm of the visual axis. What is the management?","o":["Topical antifungal drops","Observation with six-monthly monitoring","Flap lift with mechanical scraping of epithelial cells","Nd:YAG laser to the interface ingrowth","Immediate regrafting with new flap"],"a":2,"e":"Epithelial ingrowth causing visual axis involvement and reduced vision requires surgical intervention; the flap is lifted and epithelial cells are mechanically scraped from both the stromal bed and the undersurface of the flap using a spatula and cellulose sponge under irrigation.<br><br>Alcohol 20% can be applied briefly to the stromal bed to destroy residual epithelial cells before flap replacement; recurrence rates reach 30%; peripheral ingrowth not affecting vision is monitored but central ingrowth causing flap melt or vision loss requires prompt surgical removal.<br><br>Topical antifungals (A) have no role in epithelial ingrowth; observation (B) is only appropriate for peripheral ingrowth not involving the visual axis; Nd:YAG laser (D) is not effective for interface epithelial ingrowth; regrafting (E) is not indicated for epithelial ingrowth management.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 65-year-old patient receives a penetrating keratoplasty graft. Which HLA matching is most important in reducing the risk of corneal graft rejection?","o":["HLA-A matching","HLA-B matching","HLA-C matching","HLA-DR matching","ABO blood group matching"],"a":3,"e":"HLA-DR matching is the most important single HLA antigen to match in high-risk penetrating keratoplasty; studies show that HLA-DR mismatching is the strongest predictor of rejection in vascularised high-risk recipient beds where the standard immune privilege of the cornea is lost.<br><br>In normal avascular recipients HLA matching has less demonstrable benefit due to the immune-privileged status of the cornea; HLA-DR matching is specifically recommended for high-risk cases including repeat grafts, vascularised beds, and eyes with multiple prior rejection episodes.<br><br>HLA-A matching (A), HLA-B matching (B), and HLA-C matching (C) are less critical than HLA-DR; ABO blood group matching (E) is important for organ transplantation but not the primary HLA consideration in corneal graft matching protocols.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 33-year-old myope is assessed for refractive surgery. Corneal topography shows normal anterior surface but Scheimpflug tomography shows posterior elevation of plus 22 microns at the thinnest point. What is the most appropriate advice?","o":["Proceed with standard LASIK as anterior surface is normal","Proceed with PRK as it is safer than LASIK","Perform crosslinking first then LASIK after six months","Proceed with SMILE as it preserves more stroma","Decline all corneal laser refractive surgery and discuss phakic IOL"],"a":4,"e":"Posterior corneal elevation exceeding 16 microns indicates subclinical keratoconus or forme fruste keratoconus; any corneal laser refractive surgery that removes stromal tissue is absolutely contraindicated as it will precipitate rapid iatrogenic ectasia even when the anterior surface appears normal.<br><br>Phakic IOL implantation is the safest refractive option as it adds lens power without altering the corneal architecture; the patient must be counselled about the subclinical ectasia, the lifelong contraindication to corneal laser surgery, and the need for regular topographic monitoring.<br><br>Proceeding with LASIK (A) risks rapid ectasia; PRK (B) also removes stroma and is equally contraindicated; crosslinking then LASIK (C) is not an accepted protocol for subclinical keratoconus; SMILE (D) also removes stromal tissue and is contraindicated.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which investigation is most useful for detecting early keratoconus before slit-lamp signs appear?","o":["Gonioscopy","Corneal topography","Visual field testing","Schirmer test","Fluorescein angiography"],"a":1,"e":"Corneal topography maps corneal curvature and is highly sensitive for detecting early keratoconus and subclinical ectatic disorders before obvious slit-lamp findings develop.<br><br>Characteristic findings include asymmetric inferior steepening and irregular astigmatic patterns. It is essential before refractive surgery screening.<br><br>Schirmer test (D) evaluates tear production rather than corneal curvature abnormalities. Gonioscopy (A) is used to assess anterior chamber angles in glaucoma.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal investigation measures endothelial cell morphology and density?","o":["Pachymetry","Keratometry","Specular microscopy","Corneal topography","Retinoscopy"],"a":2,"e":"Specular microscopy evaluates corneal endothelial cell density, morphology, and hexagonality. It is important in endothelial disorders such as Fuchs dystrophy and before intraocular surgery.<br><br>Reduced endothelial cell counts indicate impaired endothelial reserve and increased risk of postoperative corneal edema.<br><br>Pachymetry (A) measures corneal thickness rather than endothelial cell characteristics. Keratometry (B) assesses corneal curvature only.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which stain is classically used to detect corneal epithelial defects?","o":["Rose bengal","Giemsa stain","Methylene blue","Gram stain","Fluorescein"],"a":4,"e":"Fluorescein dye stains areas of absent corneal epithelium bright green under cobalt-blue illumination and is routinely used to detect epithelial defects and ulcers.<br><br>It is particularly useful in identifying corneal abrasions, dendritic ulcers, and tear film abnormalities.<br><br>Rose bengal (A) stains devitalized epithelial cells and mucus rather than simple epithelial defects. Gram stain (D) is used for microbiological evaluation.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which investigation measures corneal thickness?","o":["Keratometry","Specular microscopy","Retinoscopy","Gonioscopy","Pachymetry"],"a":4,"e":"Pachymetry measures corneal thickness and is important in glaucoma assessment, refractive surgery planning, and ectatic disorders such as keratoconus.<br><br>Ultrasound and optical pachymetry are commonly used techniques for central corneal thickness measurement.<br><br>Keratometry (A) measures corneal curvature rather than thickness. Specular microscopy (B) evaluates endothelial cells.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which investigation is most useful for evaluating tear production in dry eye disease?","o":["Schirmer test","Keratometry","Pachymetry","Specular microscopy","Corneal topography"],"a":0,"e":"Schirmer test measures aqueous tear production using filter paper strips placed in the lower fornix. It is commonly used in dry eye evaluation.<br><br>Reduced wetting indicates deficient tear secretion and may occur in Sjögren syndrome or other tear film disorders.<br><br>Corneal topography (E) evaluates corneal curvature rather than tear secretion. Pachymetry (C) measures corneal thickness only.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal investigation evaluates anterior and posterior corneal curvature along with elevation maps?","o":["Keratometry","Corneal tomography","Schirmer test","Fluorescein staining","Specular microscopy"],"a":1,"e":"Corneal tomography provides three-dimensional imaging of anterior and posterior corneal surfaces along with pachymetric and elevation data.<br><br>It is highly valuable in diagnosing early ectatic disorders and screening refractive surgery candidates.<br><br>Keratometry (A) measures only central anterior corneal curvature and lacks posterior surface analysis. Fluorescein staining (D) evaluates epithelial defects.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which investigation is most appropriate for diagnosing fungal keratitis rapidly?","o":["Fluorescein angiography","Gonioscopy","KOH wet mount preparation","Amsler grid testing","Automated perimetry"],"a":2,"e":"Potassium hydroxide wet mount dissolves cellular debris while preserving fungal filaments, allowing rapid microscopic identification of fungal keratitis.<br><br>It is especially useful in patients with vegetative trauma and feathery corneal infiltrates.<br><br>Automated perimetry (E) evaluates visual fields rather than corneal infections. Gonioscopy (B) assesses anterior chamber angle structures.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which investigation is used to measure central corneal curvature?","o":["Keratometry","Specular microscopy","Pachymetry","Tonography","Schirmer testing"],"a":0,"e":"Keratometry measures the curvature of the central anterior corneal surface and is essential for contact lens fitting and intraocular lens calculations.<br><br>It detects regular astigmatism but has limitations in irregular corneal disorders such as advanced keratoconus.<br><br>Specular microscopy (B) evaluates endothelial cells rather than corneal curvature. Pachymetry (C) measures corneal thickness.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which dye stains devitalized epithelial cells and mucus in dry eye disease?","o":["Fluorescein","Rose bengal","Trypan blue","Indigo carmine","Gentian violet"],"a":1,"e":"Rose bengal stains devitalized epithelial cells and mucus strands, making it useful in dry eye disorders and ocular surface disease evaluation.<br><br>It highlights areas of tear film deficiency and epithelial compromise not always visible with fluorescein staining alone.<br><br>Fluorescein (A) primarily stains areas of epithelial loss rather than devitalized cells. Trypan blue (C) is commonly used during cataract surgery.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which investigation is most useful for evaluating corneal endothelial decompensation?","o":["Visual field testing","OCT macula","Retinoscopy","Gonioscopy","Specular microscopy"],"a":4,"e":"Specular microscopy evaluates endothelial cell density and morphology, which are critical in corneal endothelial disorders and surgical risk assessment.<br><br>Low endothelial counts indicate reduced pump function and predisposition to postoperative corneal edema or bullous keratopathy.<br><br>Retinoscopy (C) evaluates refractive error rather than endothelial function. OCT macula (B) assesses retinal structure instead of corneal cells.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal investigation is particularly important before LASIK surgery?","o":["Gonioscopy","Corneal topography","Automated perimetry","Color vision testing","Fundus fluorescein angiography"],"a":1,"e":"Corneal topography is essential before LASIK to identify keratoconus, forme fruste ectasia, and irregular corneal curvature patterns.<br><br>Failure to detect subtle ectatic abnormalities increases the risk of postoperative corneal ectasia after refractive surgery.<br><br>Automated perimetry (C) evaluates optic nerve function rather than corneal biomechanics. Gonioscopy (A) assesses the anterior chamber angle.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which test measures tear film stability by assessing tear breakup time?","o":["TBUT test","Keratometry","Pachymetry","Tonometry","Specular microscopy"],"a":0,"e":"Tear breakup time evaluates tear film stability by measuring the interval between blinking and appearance of dry spots after fluorescein instillation.<br><br>Short breakup time indicates tear film instability and evaporative dry eye disease.<br><br>Tonometry (D) measures intraocular pressure rather than tear film function. Pachymetry (C) measures corneal thickness only.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal investigation uses Placido disc rings?","o":["Corneal topography","Specular microscopy","Ultrasound biomicroscopy","Pachymetry","Gonioscopy"],"a":0,"e":"Placido disc-based corneal topography analyzes reflected concentric rings to map anterior corneal curvature and detect irregular astigmatism.<br><br>It is widely used in keratoconus diagnosis, contact lens fitting, and refractive surgery assessment.<br><br>Specular microscopy (B) studies endothelial cells rather than surface curvature. Ultrasound biomicroscopy (C) evaluates anterior segment structures.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which investigation is most appropriate for diagnosing Acanthamoeba keratitis?","o":["Viral culture only","Gonioscopy","Visual field testing","Electroretinography","Confocal microscopy"],"a":4,"e":"Confocal microscopy can visualize Acanthamoeba cysts and trophozoites within the cornea in vivo and is highly useful in suspected Acanthamoeba keratitis.<br><br>It is especially valuable when severe pain is disproportionate to clinical signs in contact lens wearers.<br><br>Visual field testing (C) assesses optic nerve function rather than infectious keratitis. Electroretinography (D) evaluates retinal function.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which investigation evaluates corneal sensitivity?","o":["Cochet-Bonnet esthesiometry","Schirmer testing","Keratometry","Gonioscopy","Retinoscopy"],"a":0,"e":"Cochet-Bonnet esthesiometry measures corneal sensation using a nylon filament of adjustable length applied to the corneal surface.<br><br>It is useful in herpes simplex keratitis, neurotrophic keratopathy, and trigeminal nerve disorders.<br><br>Schirmer testing (B) measures tear secretion rather than corneal sensation. Keratometry (C) evaluates corneal curvature only.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which investigation is most useful for evaluating corneal astigmatism quantitatively?","o":["Gonioscopy","Keratometry","Schirmer testing","Tonography","Electrooculography"],"a":1,"e":"Keratometry quantitatively measures central corneal curvature and helps determine the degree and axis of corneal astigmatism.<br><br>It is essential for contact lens fitting and intraocular lens power calculations before cataract surgery.<br><br>Electrooculography (E) evaluates retinal pigment epithelium function rather than corneal curvature abnormalities. Tonography (D) assesses aqueous outflow.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which investigation is most sensitive for detecting subclinical corneal ectasia?","o":["Retinoscopy","Corneal tomography","Fluorescein staining","Schirmer testing","Direct ophthalmoscopy"],"a":1,"e":"Corneal tomography provides detailed three-dimensional analysis of anterior and posterior corneal surfaces, making it highly sensitive for detecting subclinical ectasia.<br><br>Posterior elevation abnormalities may appear before obvious anterior surface changes become visible.<br><br>Retinoscopy (A) may reveal irregular reflexes but lacks the sensitivity of tomographic imaging. Fluorescein staining (C) detects epithelial defects only.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which stain is most useful for identifying herpes simplex dendritic ulcers?","o":["Rose bengal and fluorescein","Gram stain only","Giemsa stain only","Methylene blue only","Trypan blue only"],"a":0,"e":"Fluorescein stains the ulcer bed of dendritic lesions, whereas rose bengal stains the devitalized epithelial edges and terminal bulbs in herpes simplex keratitis.<br><br>Combined staining improves visualization of classic dendritic morphology and assists diagnosis.<br><br>Gram stain (B) is primarily used for bacterial identification rather than viral epithelial lesions. Trypan blue (E) is commonly used in cataract surgery.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which investigation is most appropriate for measuring endothelial cell loss after cataract surgery?","o":["Corneal topography","Keratometry","Retinoscopy","Schirmer testing","Specular microscopy"],"a":4,"e":"Specular microscopy quantifies endothelial cell density and morphology and is valuable for monitoring postoperative endothelial cell loss after cataract surgery.<br><br>Significant endothelial loss increases the risk of persistent corneal edema and pseudophakic bullous keratopathy.<br><br>Corneal topography (A) evaluates curvature rather than endothelial integrity. Schirmer testing (D) measures tear secretion.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which investigation is commonly used to assess dry eye severity by ocular surface staining score?","o":["Rose bengal staining","Gonioscopy","Retinoscopy","Keratometry","Automated perimetry"],"a":0,"e":"Rose bengal staining highlights devitalized epithelial cells and mucus on the ocular surface, helping assess severity of dry eye disease.<br><br>Increased staining indicates ocular surface damage from tear film instability or deficient tear production.<br><br>Keratometry (D) measures corneal curvature rather than epithelial integrity. Automated perimetry (E) evaluates visual fields.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which investigation provides the most detailed in vivo imaging of corneal layers at microscopic resolution?","o":["Confocal microscopy","Gonioscopy","Retinoscopy","Keratometry","Direct ophthalmoscopy"],"a":0,"e":"Confocal microscopy provides high-resolution in vivo imaging of corneal epithelium, stroma, nerves, and endothelium at near-histological detail.<br><br>It is especially useful in infectious keratitis, corneal dystrophies, and assessment of corneal nerves in neurotrophic disease.<br><br>Direct ophthalmoscopy (E) examines the retina rather than corneal microstructure. Keratometry (D) measures surface curvature only.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 55-year-old patient is assessed before cataract surgery. Specular microscopy shows endothelial cell density of 850 cells/mm2 with significant polymegathism. What does polymegathism specifically indicate?","o":["Variation in endothelial cell shape","Reduction in percentage of hexagonal cells","Variation in endothelial cell size","Presence of guttae on Descemet membrane","Reduction in endothelial cell density"],"a":2,"e":"Polymegathism refers to variation in individual endothelial cell size measured by the coefficient of variation of mean cell area; it is the earliest and most sensitive indicator of endothelial stress, occurring before significant cell density reduction becomes apparent on specular microscopy.<br><br>A coefficient of variation above 0.40 is abnormal; polymegathism indicates the endothelium is under physiological stress and is more susceptible to surgical trauma; it guides surgical planning and anaesthetic decisions before intraocular surgery.<br><br>Variation in cell shape (A) is pleomorphism not polymegathism; reduction in hexagonal cells (B) defines pleomorphism; presence of guttae (D) indicates Fuchs dystrophy specifically; reduction in cell density alone (E) is endothelial cell loss not polymegathism.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 60-year-old patient with Fuchs dystrophy undergoes specular microscopy. The percentage of hexagonal cells is 38%. What does this finding indicate?","o":["Normal endothelial morphology within acceptable limits","Normal ageing change","Isolated polymegathism without functional significance","Early keratoconus affecting the posterior corneal surface","Clinically significant pleomorphism indicating endothelial stress"],"a":4,"e":"Pleomorphism is the reduction in percentage of hexagonal cells; a normal cornea has at least 60% hexagonal cells; below 50% hexagonality is clinically significant pleomorphism indicating endothelial stress with impaired mosaic stability and increased risk of postoperative corneal decompensation after intraocular surgery.<br><br>In Fuchs dystrophy, both pleomorphism and polymegathism worsen progressively alongside guttae formation; the combination of low hexagonality, high coefficient of variation, and reduced cell density identifies corneas at highest risk of decompensation after cataract surgery.<br><br>Normal morphology (A) requires at least 60% hexagonality; isolated polymegathism (C) refers to cell size not shape variation; keratoconus (D) affects topography not specular microscopy findings; normal ageing (B) reduces hexagonality gradually but 38% is pathologically low.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 30-year-old is assessed for LASIK surgery. Keratometry readings show K1 of 48.5 dioptres and K2 of 52.0 dioptres. What does this keratometry finding suggest?","o":["Normal corneal curvature suitable for LASIK","High myopia requiring phakic IOL implantation","Normal keratometry values within accepted refractive range","Against-the-rule astigmatism only with normal steepness","Abnormally steep cornea raising suspicion for keratoconus"],"a":4,"e":"Normal corneal keratometry ranges from 41 to 46 dioptres; K2 of 52.0 dioptres is significantly above the normal range indicating an abnormally steep cornea; this finding combined with any irregular topographic pattern or inferior steepening should raise strong suspicion for keratoconus and prompt Scheimpflug tomography.<br><br>Keratometry values exceeding 47.2 dioptres are considered the upper limit of normal; LASIK is contraindicated if keratoconus is confirmed; the steep readings alone necessitate comprehensive ectasia screening before any refractive surgical decision is made.<br><br>Normal corneal curvature (A) is 41 to 46 dioptres making 52 clearly abnormal; high myopia (B) is a refractive not keratometric finding; against-the-rule astigmatism (D) does not cause steepness exceeding 52 dioptres; normal keratometry (C) is definitively excluded at 52 dioptres.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 45-year-old with suspected keratoconus undergoes Pentacam Scheimpflug tomography. Posterior corneal elevation at the thinnest point measures plus 24 microns above the best fit sphere. What is the clinical significance?","o":["Normal posterior elevation within accepted limits","Mildly elevated requiring annual monitoring only","Consistent with Fuchs endothelial dystrophy","Highly suspicious for keratoconus or subclinical ectasia","Consistent with Terrien marginal degeneration pattern"],"a":3,"e":"Posterior corneal elevation exceeding 16 microns above the best fit sphere on Scheimpflug tomography is the earliest and most sensitive indicator of keratoconus or subclinical ectasia; at plus 24 microns this patient has strongly positive posterior elevation warranting corneal refractive surgery contraindication.<br><br>Posterior elevation abnormality precedes anterior surface changes and clinical signs; the Belin-Ambrosio enhanced ectasia display combines posterior elevation, pachymetric progression, and anterior elevation into a composite score providing highest sensitivity for detecting early ectasia.<br><br>Normal posterior elevation (A) is below 16 microns; annual monitoring only (B) is insufficient for 24 microns requiring immediate refractive surgery contraindication; Fuchs dystrophy (C) affects the endothelium not posterior elevation maps; Terrien degeneration (E) is a peripheral thinning condition.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 50-year-old with a corneal ulcer has a scraping taken. KOH mount is performed. Which organism is specifically identified by KOH mount showing non-branching oval budding structures with pseudohyphae?","o":["Candida albicans","Fusarium solani","Acanthamoeba species","Aspergillus fumigatus","Mucor species"],"a":0,"e":"Candida albicans is a dimorphic fungus identified on KOH mount by oval budding yeast cells with pseudohyphae; it causes corneal ulcers in immunocompromised patients, those on prolonged antibiotics, and patients with ocular surface disease; it differs from filamentous fungi by its budding yeast morphology.<br><br>Natamycin has limited efficacy against Candida; fluconazole and voriconazole provide better antifungal coverage; the clinical presentation of Candida keratitis is typically indolent with creamy white stromal infiltrate lacking the feathery margins of filamentous fungal keratitis.<br><br>Fusarium (B) shows septate hyphae with acute angle branching; Acanthamoeba (C) shows double-walled cysts; Aspergillus (D) shows septate hyphae with dichotomous branching; Mucor (E) shows non-septate broad hyphae with right-angle branching.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Confocal microscopy is performed on a contact lens wearer with suspected Acanthamoeba keratitis. Which finding is pathognomonic on confocal microscopy?","o":["Septate hyphae in the anterior stroma","Gram-negative rod shaped bacteria within keratocytes","Highly reflective double-walled cysts within corneal stroma","Viral inclusion bodies within epithelial nuclei","Calcium deposits within Bowman layer"],"a":2,"e":"In vivo confocal microscopy reveals Acanthamoeba cysts as highly reflective double-walled round structures 15 to 25 microns in diameter within the corneal stroma; this is pathognomonic and provides an immediate non-invasive diagnosis without requiring scraping or culture.<br><br>Confocal microscopy provides the fastest diagnosis of Acanthamoeba keratitis; early identification before ring infiltrate formation dramatically improves treatment response; cysts are resistant to most antimicrobials making early diagnosis essential for initiating aggressive polyhexamethylene biguanide and chlorhexidine therapy.<br><br>Septate hyphae (A) indicate filamentous fungal keratitis; gram-negative rods (B) are not identifiable on confocal microscopy; viral inclusion bodies (D) are not visualised by confocal microscopy; calcium deposits (E) indicate band keratopathy not Acanthamoeba.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 40-year-old patient undergoes corneal topography using the Placido disc system. Which specific corneal parameter is Placido disc topography unable to assess?","o":["Anterior corneal curvature map","Simulated keratometry values","Corneal astigmatism axis and magnitude","Posterior corneal elevation and thickness profile","Central corneal power in dioptres"],"a":3,"e":"Placido disc topography analyses only the anterior corneal surface by measuring the reflection of concentric rings; it cannot assess the posterior corneal surface or provide pachymetric data; this is its fundamental limitation compared to Scheimpflug tomography which captures the full corneal profile including posterior elevation.<br><br>The inability to detect posterior corneal elevation changes means Placido topography can miss subclinical keratoconus where early changes begin on the posterior surface; Scheimpflug tomography is therefore superior for pre-refractive surgery screening detecting early ectasia.<br><br>Anterior corneal curvature (A), simulated keratometry (B), astigmatism data (C), and central corneal power (E) are all reliably measured by Placido disc topography within its anterior surface analysis capability.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 65-year-old patient is being assessed for penetrating keratoplasty. Specular microscopy of the donor cornea at the eye bank shows an endothelial cell density of 1800 cells/mm2. Is this donor suitable for transplantation?","o":["No; minimum required density is 2500 cells/mm2","No; minimum required density is 3000 cells/mm2","Borderline; acceptable only if recipient is under 40","Yes but only for DMEK not penetrating keratoplasty","Yes; 1800 cells/mm2 is within acceptable eye bank limits"],"a":4,"e":"Most eye banks accept donor corneas with endothelial cell density above 2000 cells/mm2; however standards vary and many accept corneas with density of 2000 cells/mm2 or above; 1800 cells/mm2 is marginally below most thresholds. However the accepted minimum at many centres including the Eye Bank Association of America is approximately 2000 cells/mm2.<br><br>Cell density declines further after transplantation from surgical trauma; a minimum preoperative donor density ensures sufficient reserve for long-term graft survival; donor age, death-to-preservation time, and storage duration also influence suitability alongside cell count.<br><br>2500 cells/mm2 (A) is an unnecessarily high threshold not required by most eye banks; 3000 cells/mm2 (B) is the normal young adult density not the minimum transplantation threshold; DMEK-specific restriction (D) is not the basis for this decision; recipient age (C) does not determine donor suitability independently.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 35-year-old undergoes anterior segment OCT before DMEK surgery. Which specific information does anterior segment OCT provide that is most critical for DMEK surgical planning?","o":["Endothelial cell density measurement","Corneal topographic power map","Keratocyte density in the stroma","Tear film osmolarity assessment","Anterior chamber depth and angle anatomy measurement"],"a":4,"e":"Anterior segment OCT provides high-resolution imaging of the anterior chamber depth, angle anatomy, and iridocorneal angle configuration critical for DMEK surgical planning; adequate anterior chamber depth is essential for safe graft unfolding and rebubbling manoeuvres during DMEK surgery.<br><br>It also visualises Descemet membrane detachment, graft apposition, and interface fluid in the postoperative period; serial anterior segment OCT monitoring after DMEK confirms graft attachment and detects subclinical partial detachments requiring rebubbling before vision-compromising stromal oedema develops.<br><br>Endothelial cell density (A) requires specular microscopy not OCT; corneal topographic power (B) requires topography or tomography; keratocyte density (C) requires confocal microscopy; tear film osmolarity (D) requires an osmolarity analyser not OCT.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal investigation is most useful for detecting irregular astigmatism in keratoconus?","o":["Schirmer testing","Corneal topography","Gonioscopy","Visual field analysis","Retinoscopy only"],"a":1,"e":"Corneal topography maps anterior corneal curvature and is highly effective in detecting irregular astigmatism associated with keratoconus and other ectatic disorders.<br><br>Characteristic findings include asymmetric inferior steepening and distorted bow-tie patterns. It is essential in refractive surgery screening and ectasia diagnosis.<br><br>Schirmer testing (A) evaluates tear secretion rather than corneal shape abnormalities. Gonioscopy (C) examines anterior chamber angle structures instead of corneal curvature.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which investigation is most appropriate for measuring corneal endothelial cell density before cataract surgery?","o":["Pachymetry","Keratometry","Specular microscopy","Corneal topography","Amsler grid testing"],"a":2,"e":"Specular microscopy evaluates endothelial cell density, morphology, and hexagonality, helping assess corneal endothelial reserve before intraocular surgery.<br><br>Reduced endothelial counts increase the risk of postoperative corneal edema and pseudophakic bullous keratopathy.<br><br>Pachymetry (A) measures corneal thickness rather than endothelial cell characteristics. Corneal topography (D) evaluates corneal curvature patterns.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which test is commonly used to assess tear film stability in dry eye disease?","o":["TBUT test","Gonioscopy","Fluorescein angiography","Keratometry","Electroretinography"],"a":0,"e":"Tear breakup time evaluates tear film stability by measuring the interval between blinking and appearance of dry spots after fluorescein instillation.<br><br>Short breakup time indicates unstable tear film and is commonly seen in evaporative dry eye disease and meibomian gland dysfunction.<br><br>Keratometry (D) measures corneal curvature rather than tear film function. Electroretinography (E) evaluates retinal electrical activity instead of ocular surface disease.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which investigation provides microscopic in vivo imaging of corneal nerves and infectious organisms?","o":["Corneal topography","Confocal microscopy","Retinoscopy","Schirmer testing","Direct ophthalmoscopy"],"a":1,"e":"Confocal microscopy provides high-resolution in vivo imaging of corneal layers, nerves, and microorganisms at near-histological detail.<br><br>It is particularly valuable in diagnosing Acanthamoeba keratitis, fungal keratitis, and neurotrophic corneal disorders.<br><br>Retinoscopy (C) evaluates refractive status rather than corneal microstructure. Direct ophthalmoscopy (E) is used for retinal examination instead of corneal imaging.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A contact lens wearer presents with severe pain, ring infiltrate, and pain disproportionate to clinical findings. Which diagnosis is most likely?","o":["Fungal keratitis","Marginal keratitis","Mooren ulcer","Herpes simplex keratitis","Acanthamoeba keratitis"],"a":4,"e":"Acanthamoeba keratitis is strongly associated with contact lens misuse and exposure to contaminated water. Severe pain out of proportion to slit-lamp findings is a classic feature.<br><br>Herpes simplex keratitis (D) typically produces dendritic epithelial ulcers rather than ring infiltrates with extreme pain. Marginal keratitis (B) is usually peripheral and related to blepharitis.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal dystrophy is inherited as an autosomal recessive disorder?","o":["Granular dystrophy","Lattice dystrophy","Macular dystrophy","Reis-Bücklers dystrophy","Fuchs dystrophy"],"a":2,"e":"Macular corneal dystrophy is an autosomal recessive stromal dystrophy characterized by diffuse stromal haze extending to the limbus with severe visual impairment.<br><br>It often presents earlier and progresses more aggressively than other stromal dystrophies, frequently requiring keratoplasty.<br><br>Granular dystrophy (A) and lattice dystrophy (B) are usually inherited as autosomal dominant conditions rather than autosomal recessive disorders.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which sign is classically associated with advanced keratoconus?","o":["Guttata","Hutchinson sign","Hypopyon","Arlt triangle","Munson sign"],"a":4,"e":"Munson sign refers to V-shaped protrusion of the lower eyelid during downgaze caused by advanced conical protrusion of the cornea in keratoconus.<br><br>It is considered a classic late sign of ectatic disease associated with marked stromal thinning and irregular astigmatism.<br><br>Guttata (A) are endothelial excrescences associated with Fuchs dystrophy rather than keratoconus. Hypopyon (C) indicates severe anterior segment inflammation.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which refractive surgery procedure creates a corneal flap before stromal laser ablation?","o":["PRK","SMILE","LASIK","Radial keratotomy","Corneal cross-linking"],"a":2,"e":"LASIK involves formation of a corneal flap followed by excimer laser ablation of stromal tissue to correct refractive errors such as myopia and astigmatism.<br><br>The flap is repositioned after ablation, allowing rapid visual recovery and minimal postoperative discomfort.<br><br>PRK (A) removes the epithelium without creating a stromal flap. SMILE (B) removes a stromal lenticule through a small incision.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which investigation is most sensitive for early detection of keratoconus?","o":["Gonioscopy","Corneal topography","Schirmer testing","Visual field analysis","Direct ophthalmoscopy"],"a":1,"e":"Corneal topography detects subtle corneal curvature abnormalities and asymmetric inferior steepening before clinical keratoconus becomes apparent on slit-lamp examination.<br><br>It is essential in refractive surgery screening to identify subclinical ectatic disorders and reduce postoperative ectasia risk.<br><br>Schirmer testing (C) evaluates tear secretion rather than corneal curvature. Gonioscopy (A) assesses anterior chamber angle anatomy.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal ulcer classically shows dendritic branching with terminal bulbs?","o":["Fungal ulcer","Neurotrophic ulcer","Marginal ulcer","Mooren ulcer","Herpetic ulcer"],"a":4,"e":"Herpes simplex epithelial keratitis classically presents with dendritic ulcers containing branching linear lesions and terminal bulbs visible with fluorescein staining.<br><br>Corneal sensation is often reduced because of trigeminal nerve involvement by the virus.<br><br>Fungal ulcers (A) usually demonstrate feathery borders and satellite lesions rather than branching epithelial dendrites. Mooren ulcer (D) is a peripheral autoimmune ulcerative condition.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal degeneration is caused by calcium deposition in Bowman layer?","o":["Arcus senilis","Band keratopathy","Pterygium","Lattice dystrophy","Granular dystrophy"],"a":1,"e":"Band keratopathy results from calcium salt deposition in Bowman layer and superficial cornea, producing a horizontal gray-white interpalpebral opacity.<br><br>It is associated with chronic uveitis, hypercalcemia, and longstanding ocular disease.<br><br>Arcus senilis (A) is caused by peripheral lipid deposition rather than calcium accumulation. Granular dystrophy (E) is an inherited stromal dystrophy.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which ectatic disorder classically produces crab-claw topographic appearance?","o":["Keratoconus","Keratoglobus","Posterior keratoconus","Terrien degeneration","Pellucid marginal degeneration"],"a":4,"e":"Pellucid marginal degeneration is characterized by inferior peripheral corneal thinning with protrusion just above the thinned area, producing crab-claw topographic patterns.<br><br>Patients commonly develop high against-the-rule astigmatism and progressive visual distortion.<br><br>Keratoconus (A) typically causes central or paracentral cone formation rather than inferior peripheral thinning. Keratoglobus (B) causes generalized thinning.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which procedure is specifically designed to halt progression of keratoconus?","o":["LASIK","Radial keratotomy","Corneal collagen cross-linking","Penetrating keratoplasty","SMILE"],"a":2,"e":"Corneal collagen cross-linking strengthens stromal collagen fibers using riboflavin and ultraviolet-A irradiation to stabilize progressive ectatic disease.<br><br>It significantly reduces the risk of keratoconus progression and future corneal transplantation in many patients.<br><br>LASIK (A) weakens corneal biomechanics and is contraindicated in progressive keratoconus. Radial keratotomy (B) may further destabilize the cornea.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which investigation evaluates endothelial cell density and morphology?","o":["Corneal topography","Pachymetry","Schirmer testing","Keratometry","Specular microscopy"],"a":4,"e":"Specular microscopy assesses endothelial cell density, shape, and hexagonality and is important in endothelial disorders such as Fuchs dystrophy.<br><br>Low endothelial counts indicate reduced endothelial reserve and increased risk of postoperative corneal edema.<br><br>Keratometry (D) measures corneal curvature rather than endothelial cell morphology. Pachymetry (B) measures corneal thickness only.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which organism is strongly associated with contact lens-related rapidly progressive corneal ulceration?","o":["Candida albicans","Herpes simplex virus","Pseudomonas aeruginosa","Aspergillus fumigatus","Corynebacterium diphtheriae"],"a":2,"e":"Pseudomonas aeruginosa produces aggressive suppurative keratitis with rapid stromal destruction and possible corneal perforation within a short period.<br><br>Candida albicans (A) generally produces slower fungal keratitis rather than explosive stromal melting. Herpes simplex virus (B) causes dendritic epithelial ulcers.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal dystrophy is characterized by breadcrumb-like stromal deposits?","o":["Macular dystrophy","Granular dystrophy","Lattice dystrophy","Fuchs dystrophy","Posterior polymorphous dystrophy"],"a":1,"e":"Granular dystrophy is an autosomal dominant stromal dystrophy characterized by sharply demarcated white breadcrumb or snowflake-like stromal opacities.<br><br>Intervening stroma often remains clear during early disease, preserving vision initially.<br><br>Lattice dystrophy (C) produces branching refractile stromal lines caused by amyloid deposition. Macular dystrophy (A) causes diffuse stromal haze.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which ring is produced by iron deposition around the base of the cone in keratoconus?","o":["Kayser-Fleischer ring","Weiss ring","Fleischer ring","Wessely ring","Coats ring"],"a":2,"e":"Fleischer ring is caused by iron deposition in basal epithelial cells surrounding the cone in keratoconus and is best visualized with cobalt-blue illumination.<br><br>It is one of the classic slit-lamp findings in corneal ectatic disorders.<br><br>Kayser-Fleischer ring (A) occurs in Wilson disease due to copper deposition in Descemet membrane. Weiss ring (B) is associated with posterior vitreous detachment.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which refractive surgery complication involves epithelial cells growing beneath the LASIK flap?","o":["Corneal hydrops","Hypopyon","Descemetocele","Bullous keratopathy","Epithelial ingrowth"],"a":4,"e":"Epithelial ingrowth occurs when surface epithelial cells migrate beneath the LASIK flap interface, causing visual distortion and flap complications.<br><br>Mild peripheral ingrowth may remain stable, whereas progressive central ingrowth may require flap lifting and debridement.<br><br>Corneal hydrops (A) occurs in advanced keratoconus because of Descemet membrane rupture. Bullous keratopathy (D) results from endothelial failure.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which investigation measures central corneal thickness?","o":["Pachymetry","Keratometry","Specular microscopy","Retinoscopy","Gonioscopy"],"a":0,"e":"Pachymetry measures corneal thickness and is important in glaucoma assessment, refractive surgery planning, and ectatic corneal disorders.<br><br>Thin corneas may predispose to postoperative ectasia after refractive surgery and affect intraocular pressure interpretation.<br><br>Keratometry (B) measures corneal curvature rather than thickness. Specular microscopy (C) evaluates endothelial cell characteristics.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal ulcer is strongly associated with trauma involving vegetative matter?","o":["Viral keratitis","Fungal keratitis","Marginal ulcer","Neurotrophic ulcer","Mooren ulcer"],"a":1,"e":"Fungal keratitis commonly follows trauma with vegetative matter and often presents with dry infiltrates, feathery borders, and satellite lesions.<br><br>Filamentous fungi such as Aspergillus and Fusarium are frequent causative organisms in tropical regions.<br><br>Marginal ulcers (C) are associated with staphylococcal hypersensitivity rather than vegetative trauma. Viral keratitis (A) produces dendritic lesions.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which corneal transplantation procedure preserves host endothelium?","o":["Penetrating keratoplasty","Endothelial keratoplasty","LASIK","Keratoprosthesis","Deep anterior lamellar keratoplasty"],"a":4,"e":"Deep anterior lamellar keratoplasty replaces diseased anterior stromal tissue while preserving healthy host Descemet membrane and endothelium.<br><br>Preservation of endothelium reduces risk of endothelial rejection compared with penetrating keratoplasty.<br><br>Endothelial keratoplasty (B) specifically replaces diseased endothelium rather than preserving it. LASIK (C) is a refractive procedure.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which investigation evaluates tear production quantitatively?","o":["TBUT test","Specular microscopy","Corneal topography","Keratometry","Schirmer test"],"a":4,"e":"Schirmer test quantitatively measures aqueous tear production using filter paper strips placed within the lower fornix.<br><br>Reduced wetting indicates aqueous tear deficiency and is commonly seen in Sjögren syndrome and severe dry eye disease.<br><br>TBUT test (A) evaluates tear film stability rather than total tear production. Corneal topography (C) maps corneal curvature.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which ectatic disorder presents with generalized limbus-to-limbus corneal thinning?","o":["Keratoconus","Pellucid marginal degeneration","Keratoglobus","Terrien degeneration","Posterior keratoconus"],"a":2,"e":"Keratoglobus is characterized by diffuse generalized corneal thinning involving the entire cornea from limbus to limbus with globular protrusion.<br><br>The markedly thin cornea is extremely fragile and prone to rupture after minor trauma.<br><br>Keratoconus (A) typically produces localized central or paracentral thinning rather than diffuse generalized ectasia. Pellucid degeneration (B) mainly affects inferior peripheral cornea.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which stain is most useful for identifying corneal epithelial defects?","o":["Rose bengal","Fluorescein","Giemsa stain","Gram stain","Trypan blue"],"a":1,"e":"Fluorescein dye stains areas of absent corneal epithelium bright green under cobalt-blue illumination and is routinely used to identify epithelial defects.<br><br>It is especially valuable in detecting abrasions, ulcers, and dendritic lesions in corneal disease.<br><br>Rose bengal (A) stains devitalized epithelial cells and mucus rather than simple epithelial defects. Gram stain (D) is used for microbiological analysis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 45-year-old farmer presents with a corneal ulcer after soil trauma. Scraping shows gram-positive branching filaments that are weakly acid-fast. Which organism is responsible?","o":["Nocardia asteroides","Fusarium solani","Candida albicans","Acanthamoeba species","Pseudomonas aeruginosa"],"a":0,"e":"Nocardia asteroides causes bacterial keratitis following soil trauma; gram staining shows branching filamentous gram-positive rods that are weakly acid-fast, distinguishing them from fungi identified by KOH mount.<br><br>Treatment involves intensive topical trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole or amikacin; Nocardia grows slowly on culture requiring prolonged incubation and is commonly misidentified as fungal keratitis causing diagnostic delay.<br><br>Fusarium (B) shows septate fungal hyphae; Candida (C) shows budding yeast; Acanthamoeba (D) shows double-walled cysts; Pseudomonas (E) shows gram-negative rods without branching filaments.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 35-year-old contact lens wearer presents with a ring infiltrate and extreme pain disproportionate to clinical findings. Which culture medium is most appropriate for isolating the causative organism?","o":["Lowenstein-Jensen medium","Non-nutrient agar with E. coli overlay","Chocolate agar at 37 degrees","Sabouraud dextrose agar","Blood agar at"],"a":1,"e":"Acanthamoeba requires non-nutrient agar seeded with E. coli; the organism forms clear plaques in the bacterial lawn confirming diagnosis within 24 to 72 hours; Acanthamoeba will not grow on standard bacteriological media.<br><br>Confocal microscopy is faster than culture; both should be performed simultaneously to avoid diagnostic delay in this sight-threatening condition.<br><br>Lowenstein-Jensen (A) cultures Mycobacteria; chocolate agar (C) cultures Neisseria; Sabouraud agar (D) cultures fungi; blood agar (E) cultures routine bacteria.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 55-year-old presents with a painless oval corneal ulcer inferiorly six months after trigeminal herpes zoster ophthalmicus. Corneal sensation is absent. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Bacterial suppurative keratitis","Fungal post-infectious keratitis","Acanthamoeba parasitic keratitis","Exposure interpalpebral keratitis","Neurotrophic keratitis"],"a":4,"e":"Herpes zoster ophthalmicus permanently damages corneal sensory nerves causing neurotrophic keratitis; the painless inferior ulcer with absent corneal sensation confirmed by cotton wisp testing is the classic presentation.<br><br>The Mackie classification grades severity from punctate epitheliopathy through persistent defect to stromal ulceration; cenegermin recombinant NGF drops are a modern targeted treatment.<br><br>Bacterial keratitis (A) causes pain and discharge; fungal (B) follows vegetative trauma; exposure keratitis (D) results from lagophthalmos; Acanthamoeba (C) causes severe disproportionate pain not painless ulceration.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 70-year-old with rheumatoid arthritis develops peripheral corneal melt with descemetocele. Scraping is sterile. c-ANCA is positive. Which systemic vasculitis is most likely responsible?","o":["Systemic lupus erythematosus","Polyarteritis nodosa associated","Behcet disease with oral ulcers","Granulomatosis with polyangiitis","Giant cell arteritis temporal type"],"a":3,"e":"Granulomatosis with polyangiitis causes peripheral ulcerative keratitis through c-ANCA positive immune-mediated vasculitis; sterile corneal melt in rheumatoid arthritis with positive c-ANCA strongly confirms this diagnosis.<br><br>Systemic cyclophosphamide and prednisolone are required; topical steroids alone are insufficient; tectonic keratoplasty stabilises the cornea while systemic immunosuppression controls the underlying vasculitis.<br><br>SLE (A) is ANA-positive; polyarteritis nodosa (B) is p-ANCA associated; Behcet disease (C) causes uveitis not peripheral keratitis; giant cell arteritis (E) affects large vessels not the cornea.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 25-year-old presents with map-dot-fingerprint pattern and recurrent morning pain. Rose bengal stains the map margins positively. Which layer is primarily abnormal in this dystrophy?","o":["Bowman layer","Anterior stroma","Epithelial basement membrane","Descemet membrane","Corneal endothelium"],"a":2,"e":"Epithelial basement membrane dystrophy results from abnormal reduplication of the epithelial basement membrane proliferating into the epithelium; this traps cells forming microcysts producing the map-dot-fingerprint pattern on slit-lamp examination.<br><br>Recurrent erosions occur because the abnormal basement membrane disrupts epithelial adhesion to Bowman layer; hypertonic saline, bandage contact lens, and anterior stromal puncture treat recalcitrant cases effectively.<br><br>Bowman layer (A) is affected in Reis-Bucklers dystrophy; anterior stroma (B) is affected in granular dystrophy; Descemet membrane (D) is affected in Fuchs dystrophy; endothelium (E) is not involved in this condition.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 30-year-old presents with bilateral grey-white discrete crumb-like central stromal deposits with clear intervening stroma and peripheral sparing. Histology shows bright red deposits with Masson trichrome. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Granular dystrophy type one","Macular dystrophy","Lattice dystrophy","Schnyder dystrophy","Fleck dystrophy"],"a":0,"e":"Granular dystrophy type one caused by TGFBI mutations produces discrete hyaline deposits staining bright red with Masson trichrome; clear intervening stroma and peripheral sparing are pathognomonic features distinguishing it from macular and lattice dystrophies.<br><br>Phototherapeutic keratectomy removes superficial deposits effectively; recurrence in donor graft occurs after penetrating keratoplasty; vision remains relatively preserved until deposits coalesce in later decades.<br><br>Macular dystrophy (B) shows diffuse clouding staining with Alcian blue; lattice (C) shows amyloid staining Congo red positive; Schnyder dystrophy (D) shows cholesterol crystals; fleck dystrophy (E) shows diffuse dandruff-like deposits throughout the entire stroma.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 40-year-old presents with polychromatic crystalline central corneal deposits, a dense arcus, and raised serum cholesterol. Histology shows cholesterol and phospholipid stromal deposits. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Macular dystrophy","Lattice dystrophy","Granular dystrophy","Avellino dystrophy","Schnyder corneal dystrophy"],"a":4,"e":"Schnyder corneal dystrophy caused by UBIAD1 mutations produces central disc-shaped crystalline deposits, dense arcus juvenilis, and corneal haze; systemic hypercholesterolaemia is present in over half of affected patients confirming the lipid metabolic basis.<br><br>Phototherapeutic keratectomy and penetrating keratoplasty are surgical options; lipid-lowering therapy addresses the systemic component without reversing established corneal deposits.<br><br>Macular dystrophy (A) shows glycosaminoglycan clouding; granular dystrophy (C) shows hyaline deposits with clear intervening stroma; Avellino dystrophy (D) shows combined granular and lattice features; lattice dystrophy (B) shows amyloid branching lines.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 65-year-old presents with a white horizontal band opacity across the interpalpebral cornea with Swiss-cheese holes within it. Calcium deposits are confirmed histologically. What is the treatment?","o":["Topical prednisolone drops","Penetrating keratoplasty surgery","Intrastromal antifungal injection","Photodynamic therapy sessions","EDTA chelation under anaesthesia"],"a":4,"e":"Band keratopathy results from calcium phosphate deposition in Bowman layer; EDTA chelation under topical anaesthesia dissolves calcium deposits effectively; the Swiss-cheese holes represent corneal nerve perforations through Bowman layer and are pathognomonic.<br><br>Phototherapeutic keratectomy removes residual opacity after EDTA chelation; treating the underlying cause including hypercalcaemia and chronic uveitis prevents recurrence.<br><br>Topical steroids (A) do not dissolve calcium; penetrating keratoplasty (B) is reserved for advanced visual loss; photodynamic therapy (D) has no role in band keratopathy; intrastromal injection (C) is irrelevant.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 20-year-old with atopic dermatitis and chronic eye rubbing presents with progressive inferior corneal steepening on topography and Kmax of 51 dioptres. What is the most modifiable risk factor for progression?","o":["Contact lens wear","Topical steroid use","Ultraviolet light exposure","Eye rubbing cessation","Dietary vitamin deficiency"],"a":3,"e":"Chronic vigorous eye rubbing is the most important modifiable risk factor in keratoconus; mechanical trauma releases inflammatory cytokines activating matrix metalloproteinases that degrade stromal collagen causing progressive thinning and ectasia.<br><br>Addressing underlying atopy with antihistamines reduces the itch-rub cycle; stopping eye rubbing combined with crosslinking provides the most effective combined approach to halting keratoconus progression long-term.<br><br>Contact lens wear (A) does not halt ectasia; topical steroids (B) manage atopy but do not address mechanical rubbing; UV exposure (C) has minimal evidence; dietary supplements (E) have no proven role in keratoconus prevention.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 24-year-old presents with inferior peripheral corneal thinning 1 to 2 mm from the limbus with a crab-claw topographic pattern and against-the-rule astigmatism. Fleischer ring is absent. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Keratoconus","Keratoglobus","Terrien marginal degeneration","Post-LASIK ectasia","Pellucid marginal degeneration"],"a":4,"e":"Pellucid marginal degeneration causes inferior peripheral clear corneal thinning 1 to 2 mm from the limbus; the crab-claw butterfly topographic pattern with against-the-rule astigmatism and absence of Fleischer ring distinguishes it from keratoconus definitively.<br><br>RGP contact lenses are first-line optical management; large diameter eccentric DALK or penetrating keratoplasty is required for advanced contact lens-intolerant cases.<br><br>Keratoconus (A) causes central paracentral thinning with Fleischer ring; keratoglobus (B) causes global uniform corneal thinning; Terrien degeneration (C) is superior and vascularised; post-LASIK ectasia (D) follows refractive surgery with central thinning.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 19-year-old with Down syndrome presents with progressive bilateral visual loss. Corneal topography shows inferior steepening and pachymetry reveals central thinning to 430 microns. Crosslinking is planned. What is the minimum safe corneal thickness before UV-A exposure?","o":["400 microns","350 microns","450 microns","500 microns","300"],"a":0,"e":"The Dresden crosslinking protocol requires minimum corneal thickness of 400 microns after epithelial debridement and riboflavin instillation; below this threshold UV-A penetrates to the endothelium causing irreversible endothelial cell damage and potential corneal decompensation.<br><br>For corneas thinner than 400 microns hypo-osmolar riboflavin is instilled to osmotically swell the stroma above the safety threshold before UV-A exposure begins.<br><br>350 microns (B) is critically below the safe threshold; 450 microns (C) and 500 microns (D) exceed the minimum providing additional safety margin; 300 microns (E) is absolutely contraindicated for standard crosslinking protocols.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 27-year-old develops progressive myopia and irregular astigmatism eighteen months after LASIK. Corneal topography shows inferior steepening and central thinning. Residual stromal bed was 90 microns postoperatively. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Decentred ablation zone","Post-LASIK ectasia","Primary undetected keratoconus","Diffuse lamellar keratitis","Traumatic flap dislocation"],"a":1,"e":"Post-LASIK ectasia occurs when insufficient residual stromal bed leaves the cornea biomechanically compromised; 90 microns is critically below the safe minimum of 250 to 300 microns making iatrogenic ectasia inevitable in this case.<br><br>Crosslinking halts further progression; RGP lenses or keratoplasty provide visual rehabilitation; all further corneal laser surgery is permanently contraindicated.<br><br>Decentred ablation (A) causes coma without progressive thinning; primary keratoconus (C) predates surgery; diffuse lamellar keratitis (D) presents early postoperatively with interface haze; flap dislocation (E) causes acute hazing not progressive ectasia.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 32-year-old undergoes LASIK. During surgery the microkeratome creates a buttonholed flap with a central perforation. What is the most appropriate immediate management?","o":["Complete ablation through the defect","Convert immediately to PRK ablation","Replace the flap and abort surgery","Lift edges and reduce ablation depth","Apply bandage lens and reschedule"],"a":2,"e":"A buttonhole flap must be immediately replaced and surgery aborted; attempting ablation through the perforation causes irreversible central irregular scarring and permanent visual loss from stromal disruption at the ablation zone.<br><br>PRK can be safely offered three to six months later after complete flap healing and corneal surface stabilisation; full patient counselling about the complication and alternative planning is essential.<br><br>Completing ablation through the defect (A) causes irreversible central scarring; immediate PRK conversion (B) is contraindicated through disrupted epithelium; lifting edges and proceeding (D) worsens the buttonhole; bandage contact lens alone (E) is insufficient management.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 40-year-old undergoes penetrating keratoplasty for keratoconus. At one year slit-lamp shows keratic precipitates on the donor endothelium and a line of inflammatory cells advancing across the endothelium. What is this line called?","o":["Stocker line","Ferry line","Fleischer ring","Khodadoust line","Hudson-Stahli line"],"a":3,"e":"The Khodadoust line is a line of keratic precipitates on the donor endothelium representing the advancing front of host T-lymphocytes attacking donor endothelial cells; it is the hallmark sign of endothelial rejection, the most visually devastating form of corneal graft rejection.<br><br>Emergency treatment with hourly topical prednisolone and systemic steroids can reverse rejection; each episode causes irreversible endothelial cell loss potentially leading to graft failure requiring regrafting.<br><br>Stocker line (A) is iron deposition at a pterygium head; Ferry line (B) is anterior to filtering blebs; Fleischer ring (C) is iron at the keratoconus cone base; Hudson-Stahli line (E) is a horizontal normal ageing iron line.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 33-year-old undergoes DMEK for Fuchs dystrophy. On postoperative day one the graft is 40% detached. What is the most appropriate management?","o":["Immediate donor graft exchange","Topical steroids and observation","Penetrating keratoplasty conversion","Hypertonic saline and face-down positioning","Intracameral air rebubbling with face-up positioning"],"a":4,"e":"Partial DMEK graft detachment is managed by intracameral air injection to rebubble the graft against the host Descemet membrane; the patient is positioned face-up for one hour allowing the air bubble to press the donor graft promoting adherence.<br><br>Rebubbling succeeds in the majority of cases; multiple attempts may be required; persistent detachment after two to three failed rebubbling attempts necessitates donor graft exchange surgery.<br><br>Immediate graft exchange (A) is premature before rebubbling attempts; topical steroids and observation (B) are insufficient for a detached graft; penetrating keratoplasty (C) is a last resort; hypertonic saline (D) reduces oedema but cannot reattach a detached graft.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 26-year-old myope undergoes SMILE surgery. On day three he reports significant dry eye symptoms. Compared to LASIK which specific anatomical advantage explains the lower dry eye incidence after SMILE?","o":["SMILE uses less laser energy","SMILE creates a thinner optical zone","SMILE avoids riboflavin sensitisation","SMILE uses smaller spot size ablation","SMILE preserves anterior corneal nerves through small"],"a":4,"e":"SMILE creates a lenticule extracted through a 2 to 4 mm incision without flap creation; this preserves the anterior stromal nerve plexus extensively severed by the LASIK flap, resulting in significantly lower postoperative dry eye rates and faster neurosensory recovery.<br><br>The preserved nerve architecture maintains corneal sensation, tear reflex integrity, and epithelial trophic support more effectively than LASIK making SMILE preferable for patients at high risk of dry eye disease.<br><br>Less laser energy (A) does not relate to nerve preservation; thinner optical zone (B) is a potential disadvantage; riboflavin (C) is used in crosslinking not SMILE; smaller spot size (D) does not affect nerve preservation.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 50-year-old with Fuchs dystrophy undergoes specular microscopy preoperatively. The coefficient of variation of mean cell area is 0.48. What does this specifically indicate?","o":["Normal endothelial cell morphology","Abnormal polymegathism indicating endothelial stress","Clinically significant pleomorphism below 50% hexagonality","Critical cell density below 500 cells per millimetre","Normal ageing-related change requiring no assessment"],"a":1,"e":"A coefficient of variation above 0.40 indicates abnormal polymegathism reflecting significant endothelial stress; at 0.48 this cornea is at substantially increased risk of postoperative decompensation following intraocular surgical trauma.<br><br>Polymegathism is the earliest indicator of endothelial dysfunction appearing before significant cell density reduction; it guides surgical planning indicating need for viscoelastic protection and gentle phacoemulsification technique.<br><br>Normal morphology (A) requires coefficient of variation below 0.32; pleomorphism (C) refers to hexagonal cell percentage not coefficient of variation; critical cell density (D) is a separate measurement; normal ageing (E) does not produce coefficient of variation of 0.48.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 38-year-old is assessed for refractive surgery. Scheimpflug tomography shows posterior corneal elevation of plus 22 microns at the thinnest point. Anterior surface topography appears normal. What is the most appropriate advice?","o":["Proceed with standard LASIK surgery","Proceed with PRK as safer alternative","Contraindicate all laser surgery and discuss phakic IOL","Perform crosslinking then LASIK later","Proceed with SMILE as it"],"a":2,"e":"Posterior corneal elevation exceeding 16 microns indicates subclinical keratoconus; all corneal laser refractive surgery removing stromal tissue is absolutely contraindicated as it will precipitate rapid iatrogenic ectasia regardless of normal anterior surface appearance.<br><br>Phakic IOL implantation is the safest refractive option as it adds power without altering corneal architecture; the patient requires lifelong topographic monitoring and must understand the permanent laser surgery contraindication.<br><br>Proceeding with LASIK (A) and PRK (B) risk rapid ectasia; crosslinking then LASIK (D) is not an accepted protocol for subclinical keratoconus; SMILE (E) also removes stroma and is equally contraindicated.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 30-year-old undergoes corneal confocal microscopy for suspected Acanthamoeba keratitis. Which specific finding is pathognomonic on confocal microscopy?","o":["Septate hyphae in anterior stroma","Gram-negative rods within keratocytes","Calcium deposits within Bowman layer","Highly reflective double-walled cysts within stroma","Viral inclusion bodies within"],"a":3,"e":"In vivo confocal microscopy reveals Acanthamoeba cysts as highly reflective double-walled round structures 15 to 25 microns in diameter within the corneal stroma; this finding is pathognomonic providing immediate non-invasive diagnosis without requiring corneal scraping.<br><br>Early diagnosis before ring infiltrate formation dramatically improves treatment response; cysts are resistant to most antimicrobials making early aggressive polyhexamethylene biguanide and chlorhexidine therapy essential for successful outcomes.<br><br>Septate hyphae (A) indicate filamentous fungal keratitis; gram-negative rods (B) are not visible on confocal microscopy; calcium deposits (C) indicate band keratopathy; viral inclusion bodies (E) are not visualised by confocal microscopy.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 55-year-old is assessed preoperatively before DMEK surgery. Anterior segment OCT shows anterior chamber depth of 2.1 mm. What is the most important implication of this finding for DMEK surgery?","o":["Increased risk of graft rejection","Higher endothelial cell density required","Phakic IOL implantation contraindicated","Need for modified technique due to shallow chamber","Corneal crosslinking required"],"a":3,"e":"Anterior chamber depth of 2.1 mm is shallow and poses significant challenges for DMEK surgery; graft unfolding requires adequate space and a shallow chamber limits manoeuvring room making modified unfolding approaches necessary.<br><br>Combined phacoemulsification deepening the anterior chamber before DMEK insertion may be considered; preoperative anterior segment OCT identifying shallow chambers allows surgical planning preventing intraoperative complications.<br><br>Increased rejection risk (A) is unrelated to anterior chamber depth; higher cell density (B) is determined by donor characteristics; phakic IOL contraindication (C) relates to anterior chamber depth but is not the primary implication here; crosslinking (E) is irrelevant to DMEK planning.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
];